# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eppo-code
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] As of 2021, small farms, of which the vast majority are one hectare (about 2.5 acres) or smaller, produce about one-third of the world's food.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Moreover, five of every six farms in the world consist of fewer than 2 hectares (4.9 acres) and take up only around 12% of all agricultural land.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In terms of total land use, large farms are dominant.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] While only 1% of all farms globally are greater than 50 hectares (120 acres), they encompass more than 70% of the world's farmland.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Further, nearly 40% of all global agricultural land is found on farms larger than 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Farms and farming greatly influence rural economics and greatly shape rural society, affecting both the direct agricultural workforce and broader businesses that support the farms and farming populations.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The major agricultural products can be broadly grouped into foods, fibers, fuels, and raw materials (such as rubber and timber).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Food classes include cereals (grains), vegetables, fruits, cooking oils, meat, milk, eggs, and fungi.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Global agricultural production amounts to approximately 11 billion tonnes of food, 32 million tonnes of natural fibers and 4 billion m3 of wood.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] However, around 14% of the world's food is lost from production before reaching the retail level.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Modern agronomy, plant breeding, agrochemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers, and technological developments have sharply increased crop yields, but also contributed to ecological and environmental damage.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Selective breeding and modern practices in animal husbandry have similarly increased the output of meat, but have raised concerns about animal welfare and environmental damage.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Environmental issues include contributions to climate change, depletion of aquifers, deforestation, antibiotic resistance, and other agricultural pollution.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is both a cause of and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation, and climate change, all of which can cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms are widely used, although some countries ban them.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The word *agriculture* is a late Middle English adaptation of Latin *agricultūra*, from *ager* 'field' and *cultūra* 'cultivation' or 'growing'.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is defined with varying scopes, in its broadest sense using natural resources to "produce commodities which maintain life, including food, fiber, forest products, horticultural crops, and their related services".
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Thus defined, it includes arable farming, horticulture, animal husbandry and forestry, but horticulture and forestry are in practice often excluded.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] It may also be broadly decomposed into **plant agriculture**, which concerns the cultivation of useful plants, and **animal agriculture**, the production of agricultural animals.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] While agriculture usually refers to human activities, other species have been cultivating crops for up to 60 million years, such as some ant (see agriculture in ants), termite and beetle.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The development of agriculture enabled the human population to grow many times larger than could be sustained by hunting and gathering.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agriculture began independently in different parts of the globe, and included a diverse range of taxa, in at least 11 separate centers of origin.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Wild grains were collected and eaten from at least 105,000 years ago.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In the Paleolithic Levant, 23,000 years ago, cereals cultivation of emmer, barley, and oats has been observed near the sea of Galilee.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Rice was domesticated in China between 11,500 and 6200 BC with the earliest known cultivation from 5700 BC, followed by mung, soy and azuki beans.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Sheep were domesticated in Mesopotamia between 13,000 and 11,000 years ago.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Cattle were domesticated from the wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan some 10,500 years ago.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Pig production emerged in Eurasia, including Europe, East Asia and Southwest Asia, where wild boar were first domesticated about 10,500 years ago.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In the Andes of South America, the potato was domesticated between 10,000 and 7,000 years ago, along with beans, coca, llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Sugarcane and some root vegetables were domesticated in New Guinea around 9,000 years ago.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Sorghum was domesticated in the Sahel region of Africa by 7,000 years ago.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 5,600 years ago, and was independently domesticated in Eurasia.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In Mesoamerica, wild teosinte was bred into maize (corn) from 10,000 to 6,000 years ago.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The horse was domesticated in the Eurasian Steppes around 3500 BC.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Scholars have offered multiple hypotheses to explain the historical origins of agriculture.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Studies of the transition from hunter-gatherer to agricultural societies indicate an initial period of intensification and increasing sedentism; examples are the Natufian culture in the Levant, and the Early Chinese Neolithic in China.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Then, wild stands that had previously been harvested started to be planted, and gradually came to be domesticated.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In Eurasia, the Sumerians started to live in villages from about 8000 BC, relying on the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and a canal system for irrigation.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Ploughs appear in pictographs around 3000 BC; seed-ploughs around 2300 BC.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Farmers grew wheat, barley, vegetables such as lentils and onions, and fruits including dates, grapes, and figs.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Ancient Egyptian agriculture relied on the Nile River and its seasonal flooding.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Farming started in the predynastic period at the end of the Paleolithic, after 10,000 BC.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Staple food crops were grains such as wheat and barley, alongside industrial crops such as flax and papyrus.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In India, wheat, barley and jujube were domesticated by 9000 BC, soon followed by sheep and goats.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Cattle, sheep and goats were domesticated in Mehrgarh culture by 8000–6000 BC.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Cotton was cultivated by the 5th–4th millennium BC.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Archeological evidence indicates an animal-drawn plough from 2500 BC in the Indus Valley civilization.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In China, from the 5th century BC, there was a nationwide granary system and widespread silk farming.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Water-powered grain mills were in use by the 1st century BC, followed by irrigation.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] By the late 2nd century, heavy ploughs had been developed with iron ploughshares and mouldboards.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Asian rice was domesticated 8,200–13,500 years ago – depending on the molecular clock estimate that is used– on the Pearl River in southern China with a single genetic origin from the wild rice *Oryza rufipogon*.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In Greece and Rome, the major cereals were wheat, emmer, and barley, alongside vegetables including peas, beans, and olives.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Sheep and goats were kept mainly for dairy products.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In the Americas, crops domesticated in Mesoamerica (apart from teosinte) include squash, beans, and cacao.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Cocoa was domesticated by the Mayo Chinchipe of the upper Amazon around 3000 BC.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The turkey was probably domesticated in Mexico or the American Southwest.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The Aztecs developed irrigation systems, formed terraced hillsides, fertilized their soil, and developed chinampas or artificial islands.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The Mayas used extensive canal and raised field systems to farm swampland from 400 BC.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In South America agriculture may have begun about 9000 BC with the domestication of squash (Cucurbita) and other plants.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Coca was domesticated in the Andes, as were the peanut, tomato, tobacco, and pineapple.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 3600 BC.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Animals including llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs were domesticated there.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In North America, the indigenous people of the East domesticated crops such as sunflower, tobacco, squash and *Chenopodium*.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Wild foods including wild rice and maple sugar were harvested.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The domesticated strawberry is a hybrid of a Chilean and a North American species, developed by breeding in Europe and North America.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The indigenous people of the Southwest and the Pacific Northwest practiced forest gardening and fire-stick farming.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The natives controlled fire on a regional scale to create a low-intensity fire ecology that sustained a low-density agriculture in loose rotation; a sort of "wild" permaculture.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] A system of companion planting called the Three Sisters was developed in North America.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The three crops were winter squash, maize, and climbing beans.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Indigenous Australians, long supposed to have been nomadic hunter-gatherers, practiced systematic burning, possibly to enhance natural productivity in fire-stick farming.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Scholars have pointed out that hunter-gatherers need a productive environment to support gathering without cultivation.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Because the forests of New Guinea have few food plants, early humans may have used "selective burning" to increase the productivity of the wild karuka fruit trees to support the hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The Gunditjmara and other groups developed eel farming and fish trapping systems from some 5,000 years ago.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] There is evidence of 'intensification' across the whole continent over that period.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In two regions of Australia, the central west coast and eastern central, early farmers cultivated yams, native millet, and bush onions, possibly in permanent settlements.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In the Middle Ages, compared to the Roman period, agriculture in Western Europe became more focused on self-sufficiency.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The agricultural population under feudalism was typically organized into manors consisting of several hundred or more acres of land presided over by a lord of the manor with a Roman Catholic church and priest.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Thanks to the exchange with the Al-Andalus where the Arab Agricultural Revolution was underway, European agriculture transformed, with improved techniques and the diffusion of crop plants, including the introduction of sugar, rice, cotton and fruit trees (such as the orange).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] After 1492, the Columbian exchange brought New World crops such as maize, potatoes, tomatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc to Europe, and Old World crops such as wheat, barley, rice, and turnips, and livestock (including horses, cattle, sheep and goats) to the Americas.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Irrigation, crop rotation, and fertilizers advanced from the 17th century with the British Agricultural Revolution, allowing global population to rise significantly.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Since 1900, agriculture in developed nations, and to a lesser extent in the developing world, has seen large rises in productivity as mechanization replaces human labor, and assisted by synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and selective breeding.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The Haber-Bosch method allowed the synthesis of ammonium nitrate fertilizer on an industrial scale, greatly increasing crop yields and sustaining a further increase in global population.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Pastoralism involves managing domesticated animals.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In nomadic pastoralism, herds of livestock are moved from place to place in search of pasture, fodder, and water.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced in arid and semi-arid regions of Sahara, Central Asia and some parts of India.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In shifting cultivation, a small area of forest is cleared by cutting and burning the trees.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The cleared land is used for growing crops for a few years until the soil becomes too infertile, and the area is abandoned.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Another patch of land is selected and the process is repeated.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced mainly in areas with abundant rainfall where the forest regenerates quickly.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This practice is used in Northeast India, Southeast Asia, and the Amazon Basin.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Subsistence farming is practiced to satisfy family or local needs alone, with little left over for transport elsewhere.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] It is intensively practiced in Monsoon Asia and South-East Asia.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] An estimated 2.5 billion subsistence farmers worked in 2018, cultivating about 60% of the earth's arable land.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Intensive farming is cultivation to maximize productivity, with a low fallow ratio and a high use of inputs (water, fertilizer, pesticide and automation).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] It is practiced mainly in developed countries.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] From the twentieth century onwards, intensive agriculture increased crop productivity.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] It substituted synthetic fertilizers and pesticides for labor, but caused increased water pollution, and often involved farm subsidies.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Soil degradation and diseases such as stem rust are major concerns globally; approximately 40% of the world's agricultural land is seriously degraded.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Modern agriculture has raised or encountered ecological, political, and economic issues including water pollution, biofuels, genetically modified organisms, tariffs and farm subsidies, leading to alternative approaches such as the organic movement.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Unsustainable farming practices in North America led to the Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In recent years there has been a backlash against the environmental effects of conventional agriculture, resulting in the organic, regenerative, and sustainable agriculture movements.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] One of the major forces behind this movement has been the European Union, which first certified organic food in 1991 and began reform of its Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) in 2005 to phase out commodity-linked farm subsidies, also known as decoupling.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The growth of organic farming has renewed research in alternative technologies such as integrated pest management, selective breeding, and controlled-environment agriculture.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] There are concerns about the lower yield associated with organic farming and its impact on global food security.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Recent mainstream technological developments include genetically modified food.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] During the 60-year period between 1964 and 2023, most of the increase in agricultural production was achieved through intensification, while the expansion of agricultural land was limited to just 8%.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In the twenty-first century, between 2001 and 2023, global agricultural area decreased by 78 million hectares (Mha) (−2%), with cropland area increasing by 78 Mha and permanent meadows and pastures decreasing by 151 Mha.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] These changes exhibit significant regional variations.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa witnessed cropland expansion of 69 Mha accompanied by 72 Mha of forest loss, while Latin America saw 25 Mha of cropland growth alongside 85 Mha of net forest area loss.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion remains the primary driver of global deforestation, accounting for nearly 90% of forest loss.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In this century, another important aspect to consider is that approximately 3.6 Mha of croplands are abandoned annually, with land degradation likely playing a significant role in these losses.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] By 2015, the agricultural output of China was the largest in the world, followed by the European Union, India and the United States.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Economists measure the total factor productivity of agriculture, according to which agriculture in the United States is roughly 1.7 times more productive than it was in 1948.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agriculture employed 873 million people in 2021, or 27% of the global workforce, 916 million in 2023, compared with 1 027 million (or 40%) in 2000.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The share of agriculture in global GDP was stable at around 4% since 2000–2023.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Despite increases in agricultural production and productivity, between 702 and 828 million people were affected by hunger in 2021.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Food insecurity and malnutrition can be the result of conflict, climate extremes and variability and economic swings.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] It can also be caused by a country's structural characteristics such as income status and natural resource endowments as well as its political economy.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Pesticide use in agriculture went up 62% between 2000 and 2021, with the Americas accounting for half the use in 2021.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The International Fund for Agricultural Development posits that an increase in smallholder agriculture may be part of the solution to concerns about food prices and overall food security, given the favorable experience of Vietnam.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agriculture provides about one-quarter of all global employment, more than half in sub-Saharan Africa and almost 60 percent in low-income countries.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] As countries develop, other jobs have historically pulled workers away from agriculture, and labor-saving innovations increase agricultural productivity by reducing labor requirements per unit of output.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Over time, a combination of labor supply and labor demand trends have driven down the share of population employed in agriculture.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] During the 16th century in Europe, between 55 and 75% of the population was engaged in agriculture; by the 19th century, this had dropped to between 35 and 65%.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In the same countries today, the figure is less than 10%.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] At the start of the 21st century, some one billion people, or over 1/3 of the available work force, were employed in agriculture.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This constitutes approximately 70% of the global employment of children, and in many countries constitutes the largest percentage of women of any industry.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The service sector overtook the agricultural sector as the largest global employer in 2007.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In many developed countries, immigrants help fill labor shortages in high-value agriculture activities that are difficult to mechanize.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Foreign farm workers from mostly Eastern Europe, North Africa and South Asia constituted around one-third of the salaried agricultural workforce in Spain, Italy, Greece and Portugal in 2013.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Around the world, women make up a large share of the population employed in agriculture.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This share is growing in all developing regions except East and Southeast Asia where women already make up about 50 percent of the agricultural workforce.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Women make up 47 percent of the agricultural workforce in sub-Saharan Africa, a rate that has not changed significantly in the past few decades.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Women who work in agricultural production tend to do so under highly unfavorable conditions.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] They tend to be concentrated in the poorest countries, where alternative livelihoods are not available, and they maintain the intensity of their work in conditions of climate-induced weather shocks and in situations of conflict.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Women are less likely to participate as entrepreneurs and independent farmers and are engaged in the production of less lucrative crops.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The gender gap in land productivity between female- and male managed farms of the same size is 24 percent.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] On average, women earn 18.4 percent less than men in wage employment in agriculture; this means that women receive 82 cents for every dollar earned by men.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Progress has been slow in closing gaps in women's access to irrigation and in ownership of livestock, too.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Women in agriculture still have significantly less access than men to inputs, including improved seeds, fertilizers and mechanized equipment.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] On a positive note, the gender gap in access to mobile internet in low- and middle-income countries fell from 25 percent to 16 percent between 2017 and 2021, and the gender gap in access to bank accounts narrowed from 9 to 6 percentage points.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Women are as likely as men to adopt new technologies when the necessary enabling factors are put in place and they have equal access to complementary resources.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agriculture, specifically farming, remains a hazardous industry, and farmers worldwide remain at high risk of work-related injuries, lung disease, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, as well as certain cancers related to chemical use and prolonged sun exposure.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] On industrialized farms, injuries frequently involve the use of agricultural machinery, and a common cause of fatal agricultural injuries in developed countries is tractor rollovers.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Pesticides and other chemicals used in farming can be hazardous to worker health, and workers exposed to pesticides may experience illness or have children with birth defects.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] As an industry in which families commonly share in work and live on the farm itself, entire families can be at risk for injuries, illness, and death.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Ages 0–6 may be an especially vulnerable population in agriculture; common causes of fatal injuries among young farm workers include drowning, machinery and motor accidents, including with all-terrain vehicles.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Occupational fatality data from the last decade indicate that, when looking at all industries, agriculture had the leading number of work-related deaths for youth.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Within this industry, youth between the ages of 10 and 15 suffered the most non-fatal work-related injuries.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] While farming is hazardous, studies have looked at the fact that there are also many benefits to growing up and living on a farm.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The International Labor Organization considers agriculture "one of the most hazardous of all economic sectors".
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] It estimates that the annual work-related death toll among agricultural employees is at least 170,000, twice the average rate of other jobs.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In addition, incidences of death, injury and illness related to agricultural activities often go unreported.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The organization has developed the Safety and Health in Agriculture Convention, 2001, which covers the range of risks in the agriculture occupation, the prevention of these risks and the role that individuals and organizations engaged in agriculture should play.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In the United States, agriculture has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda to identify and provide intervention strategies for occupational health and safety issues.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In the European Union, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work has issued guidelines on implementing health and safety directives in agriculture, livestock farming, horticulture, and forestry.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The Agricultural Safety and Health Council of America (ASHCA) also holds a yearly summit to discuss safety.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Extending over 4.8 billion ha in 2025 – the equivalent of one-third of the Earth's land surface – agriculture has a greater impact on land and water resources compared with any other economic sector.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Pressure on land, soil and water resources has seriously compromised the performance and future prospects of agriculture, resulting in further loss of productive land and reduced water availability for farming and other forms of agricultural production.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion drives deforestation and is one of the primary causes of the degradation of carbon-rich ecosystems such as peatlands.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] An estimated 64% of agricultural land is at risk of pesticide pollution, which damages biodiversity by destroying pollinators, harms soil microbiota and makes agrifood systems less resilient to pests, pathogens and climate change.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Accounting for 72% of global freshwater withdrawals, a figure predicted to rise further in the future, agriculture contributes to and is increasingly affected by water scarcity.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Overexploitation of groundwater and seawater intrusion in coastal aquifers is widespread, with major implications for food security.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Overall production varies by country as listed.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Cropping systems vary among farms depending on the available resources and constraints; geography and climate of the farm; government policy; economic, social and political pressures; and the philosophy and culture of the farmer.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Shifting cultivation (or slash and burn) is a system in which forests are burnt, releasing nutrients to support cultivation of annual and then perennial crops for a period of several years.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Then the plot is left fallow to regrow forest, and the farmer moves to a new plot, returning after many more years (10–20).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This fallow period is shortened if population density grows, requiring the input of nutrients (fertilizer or manure) and some manual pest control.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Annual cultivation is the next phase of intensity in which there is no fallow period.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This requires even greater nutrient and pest control inputs.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Further industrialization led to the use of monocultures, when one cultivar is planted on a large acreage.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Because of the low biodiversity, nutrient use is uniform and pests tend to build up, necessitating the greater use of pesticides and fertilizers.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Multiple cropping, in which several crops are grown sequentially in one year, and intercropping, when several crops are grown at the same time, are other kinds of annual cropping systems known as polycultures.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In subtropical and arid environments, the timing and extent of agriculture may be limited by rainfall, either not allowing multiple annual crops in a year, or requiring irrigation.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In all of these environments perennial crops are grown (coffee, chocolate) and systems are practiced such as agroforestry.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In temperate environments, where ecosystems were predominantly grassland or prairie, highly productive annual farming is the dominant agricultural system.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Important categories of food crops include cereals, legumes, forage, fruits and vegetables.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Natural fibers include cotton, wool, hemp, silk and flax.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Specific crops are cultivated in distinct growing regions throughout the world.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Production is listed in millions of metric tons, based on FAO estimates.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Animal husbandry is the breeding and raising of animals for meat, milk, eggs, or wool, and for work and transport.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Working animals, including horses, mules, oxen, water buffalo, camels, llamas, alpacas, donkeys, and dogs, have for centuries been used to help cultivate fields, harvest crops, wrangle other animals, and transport farm products to buyers.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Livestock production systems can be defined based on feed source, as grassland-based, mixed, and landless.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] As of 2010, 30% of Earth's ice- and water-free area was used for producing livestock, with the sector employing approximately 1.3 billion people.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Between the 1960s and the 2000s, there was a significant increase in livestock production, both by numbers and by carcass weight, especially among beef, pigs and chickens, the latter of which had production increased by almost a factor of 10.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Non-meat animals, such as milk cows and egg-producing chickens, also showed significant production increases.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Global cattle, sheep and goat populations are expected to continue to increase sharply through 2050.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Aquaculture or fish farming, the production of fish for human consumption in confined operations, is one of the fastest growing sectors of food production, growing at an average of 9% a year between 1975 and 2007.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] During the second half of the 20th century, producers using selective breeding focused on creating livestock breeds and crossbreeds that increased production, while mostly disregarding the need to preserve genetic diversity.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This trend has led to a significant decrease in genetic diversity and resources among livestock breeds, leading to a corresponding decrease in disease resistance and local adaptations previously found among traditional breeds.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Grassland based livestock production relies upon plant material such as shrubland, rangeland, and pastures for feeding ruminant animals.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Outside nutrient inputs may be used, however manure is returned directly to the grassland as a major nutrient source.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This system is particularly important in areas where crop production is not feasible because of climate or soil, representing 30–40 million pastoralists.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Mixed production systems use grassland, fodder crops and grain feed crops as feed for ruminant and monogastric (one stomach; mainly chickens and pigs) livestock.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Manure is typically recycled in mixed systems as a fertilizer for crops.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Landless systems rely upon feed from outside the farm, representing the de-linking of crop and livestock production found more prevalently in Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development member countries.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Synthetic fertilizers are more heavily relied upon for crop production and manure use becomes a challenge as well as a source for pollution.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Industrialized countries use these operations to produce much of the global supplies of poultry and pork.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Scientists estimate that 75% of the growth in livestock production between 2003 and 2030 will be in confined animal feeding operations, sometimes called factory farming.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Much of this growth is happening in developing countries in Asia, with much smaller amounts of growth in Africa.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Some of the practices used in commercial livestock production, including the usage of growth hormones, are controversial.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Tillage is the practice of breaking up the soil with tools such as the plow or harrow to prepare for planting, for nutrient incorporation, or for pest control.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Tillage varies in intensity from conventional to no-till.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] It can improve productivity by warming the soil, incorporating fertilizer and controlling weeds, but also renders soil more prone to erosion, triggers the decomposition of organic matter releasing CO2, and reduces the abundance and diversity of soil organisms.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Pest control includes the management of weeds, insects, mites, and diseases.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Chemical (pesticides), biological (biocontrol), mechanical (tillage), and cultural practices are used.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Cultural practices include crop rotation, culling, cover crops, intercropping, composting, avoidance, and resistance.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Integrated pest management attempts to use all of these methods to keep pest populations below the number which would cause economic loss, and recommends pesticides as a last resort.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Nutrient management includes both the source of nutrient inputs for crop and livestock production, and the method of use of manure produced by livestock.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Nutrient inputs can be chemical inorganic fertilizers, manure, green manure, compost and minerals.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Crop nutrient use may also be managed using cultural techniques such as crop rotation or a fallow period.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Manure is used either by holding livestock where the feed crop is growing, such as in managed intensive rotational grazing, or by spreading either dry or liquid formulations of manure on cropland or pastures.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Water management is needed where rainfall is insufficient or variable, which occurs to some degree in most regions of the world.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Some farmers use irrigation to supplement rainfall.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In other areas such as the Great Plains in the US and Canada, farmers use a fallow year to conserve soil moisture for the following year.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Recent technological innovations in precision agriculture allow for water status monitoring and automate water usage, leading to more efficient management.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agriculture represents 70% of freshwater use worldwide.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] However, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture vary significantly by income level.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In least developed countries and landlocked developing countries, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture are as high as 90 percent of total water withdrawals and about 60 percent in Small Island Developing States.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] According to 2014 report by the International Food Policy Research Institute, agricultural technologies will have the greatest impact on food production if adopted in combination with each other.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Payment for ecosystem services is a method of providing additional incentives to encourage farmers to conserve some aspects of the environment.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Measures might include paying for reforestation upstream of a city, to improve the supply of fresh water.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Different definitions exist for agricultural automation and for the variety of tools and technologies that are used to automate production.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] One view is that agricultural automation refers to autonomous navigation by robots without human intervention.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Alternatively, it is defined as the accomplishment of production tasks through mobile, autonomous, decision-making, mechatronic devices.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] However, FAO finds that these definitions do not capture all the aspects and forms of automation, such as robotic milking machines that are static, most motorized machinery that automates the performing of agricultural operations, and digital tools (e.g., sensors) that automate only diagnosis.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] FAO defines agricultural automation as the use of machinery and equipment in agricultural operations to improve their diagnosis, decision-making or performing, reducing the drudgery of agricultural work or improving the timeliness, and potentially the precision, of agricultural operations.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has involved a progressive move from manual tools to animal traction, to motorized mechanization, to digital equipment and finally, to robotics with artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Precision agriculture often employs such automation technologies.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Motorized machines are increasingly complemented, or even superseded, by new digital equipment that automates diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] A conventional tractor, for example, can be converted into an automated vehicle allowing it to sow a field autonomously.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization has increased significantly across the world in recent years, although reliable global data with broad country coverage exist only for tractors and only up to 2009.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Global automatic milking system sales have increased over recent years, but adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Measuring the overall employment impacts of agricultural automation is difficult because it requires large amounts of data tracking all the transformations and the associated reallocation of workers both upstream and downstream.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] While automation technologies reduce labor needs for the newly automated tasks, they also generate new labor demand for other tasks, such as equipment maintenance and operation.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agricultural automation can also stimulate employment by allowing producers to expand production and by creating other agrifood systems jobs.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This is especially true when it happens in context of rising scarcity of rural labor, as is the case in high-income countries and many middle-income countries.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] On the other hand, if forcedly promoted, for example through government subsidies in contexts of abundant rural labor, it can lead to labor displacement and falling or stagnant wages, particularly affecting poor and low-skilled workers.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Climate change and agriculture are interrelated on a global scale.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Global warming is already affecting agriculture, with effects unevenly distributed across the world.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In a 2022 report, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change describes how human-induced warming has slowed growth of agricultural productivity over the past 50 years in mid and low latitudes.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Methane emissions have negatively impacted crop yields by increasing temperatures and surface ozone concentrations.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Warming is also negatively affecting crop and grassland quality and harvest stability.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Ocean warming has decreased sustainable yields of some wild fish populations while ocean acidification and warming have already affected farmed aquatic species.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Climate change will probably increase the risk of food insecurity for some vulnerable groups, such as the poor.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In order to meet the demands of a growing global population, agriculture needs to produce about 50% more food, feed and fibre by 2050 compared with the volumes it generated in 2012, according to estimates by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Achieving such objectives will place additional pressure on the world's already overstretched water, land and soil resources.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Crop alteration has been practiced by humankind for thousands of years, since the beginning of civilization.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Altering crops through breeding practices changes the genetic make-up of a plant to develop crops with more beneficial characteristics for humans, for example, larger fruits or seeds, drought-tolerance, or resistance to pests.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Significant advances in plant breeding ensued after the work of geneticist Gregor Mendel.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] His work on dominant and recessive alleles, although initially largely ignored for almost 50 years, gave plant breeders a better understanding of genetics and breeding techniques.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Crop breeding includes techniques such as plant selection with desirable traits, self-pollination and cross-pollination, and molecular techniques that genetically modify the organism.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Domestication of plants has, over the centuries increased yield, improved disease resistance and drought tolerance, eased harvest and improved the taste and nutritional value of crop plants.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Careful selection and breeding have had enormous effects on the characteristics of crop plants.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Plant selection and breeding in the 1920s and 1930s improved pasture (grasses and clover) in New Zealand.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Extensive X-ray and ultraviolet induced mutagenesis efforts (i.e. primitive genetic engineering) during the 1950s produced the modern commercial varieties of grains such as wheat, corn (maize) and barley.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The Green Revolution popularized the use of conventional hybridization to sharply increase yield by creating "high-yielding varieties".
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] For example, average yields of corn (maize) in the US have increased from around 2.5 tons per hectare (t/ha) (40 bushels per acre) in 1900 to about 9.4 t/ha (150 bushels per acre) in 2001.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Similarly, worldwide average wheat yields have increased from less than 1 t/ha in 1900 to more than 2.5 t/ha in 1990.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] South American average wheat yields are around 2 t/ha, African under 1 t/ha, and Egypt and Arabia up to 3.5 to 4 t/ha with irrigation.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In contrast, the average wheat yield in countries such as France is over 8 t/ha.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Variations in yields are due mainly to variation in climate, genetics, and the level of intensive farming techniques (use of fertilizers, chemical pest control, and growth control to avoid lodging).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Investments into innovation for agriculture are long term.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] This is because it takes time for research to become commercialized and for technology to be adapted to meet multiple regions' needs, as well as meet national guidelines before being adopted and planted in a farmer's fields.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] For instance, it took at least 60 years from the introduction of hybrid corn technology before its adoption became widespread.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Agricultural innovation developed for the specific agroecological conditions of one region is not easily transferred and used in another region with different agroecological conditions.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Instead, the innovation would have to be adapted to the specific conditions of that other region and respect its biodiversity and environmental requirements and guidelines.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Some such adaptations can be seen through the steadily increasing number of plant varieties protected under the plant variety protection instrument administered by the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms (GMO) are organisms whose genetic material has been altered by genetic engineering techniques generally known as recombinant DNA technology.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Genetic engineering has expanded the genes available to breeders to use in creating desired germlines for new crops.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Increased durability, nutritional content, insect and virus resistance and herbicide tolerance are a few of the attributes bred into crops through genetic engineering.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] For some, GMO crops cause food safety and food labeling concerns.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Numerous countries have placed restrictions on the production, import or use of GMO foods and crops.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] The Biosafety Protocol, an international treaty, regulates the trade of GMOs.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] There is ongoing discussion regarding the labeling of foods made from GMOs, and the EU has had GMO food labeling requirements since 1997.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] As of 2022, the United States requires food containing GMO ingredients to be labeled as well.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-resistant seeds have a gene implanted into their genome that allows the plants to tolerate exposure to herbicides, including glyphosate.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] These seeds allow the farmer to grow a crop that can be sprayed with herbicides to control weeds without harming the resistant crop.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-tolerant crops are used by farmers worldwide.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] With the increasing use of herbicide-tolerant crops, comes an increase in the use of glyphosate-based herbicide sprays.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In some areas glyphosate resistant weeds have developed, causing farmers to switch to other herbicides.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Some studies also link widespread glyphosate usage to iron deficiencies in some crops, which is both a crop production and a nutritional quality concern, with potential economic and health implications.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Other GMO crops used by growers include insect-resistant crops, which have a gene from the soil bacterium *Bacillus thuringiensis* (Bt), which produces a toxin specific to insects.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] Some believe that similar or better pest-resistance traits can be acquired through traditional breeding practices, and resistance to various pests can be gained through hybridization or cross-pollination with wild species.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p01] In some cases, wild species are the primary source of resistance traits; some tomato cultivars that have gained resistance to at least 19 diseases did so through crossing with wild populations of tomatoes.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is both a cause of environmental degradation and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation and climate change, which cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is one of the most important drivers of environmental pressures, particularly habitat change, climate change, water use and toxic emissions.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is the main source of toxins released into the environment, including insecticides, especially those used on cotton.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The 2011 UNEP Green Economy report stated that agricultural operations produced some 13 percent of anthropogenic global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] This includes gases from the use of inorganic fertilizers, agro-chemical pesticides, and herbicides, as well as fossil fuel-energy inputs.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agriculture imposes multiple external costs upon society through effects such as pesticide damage to nature (especially herbicides and insecticides), nutrient runoff, excessive water usage, and loss of natural environment.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] A 2000 assessment of agriculture in the UK determined total external costs for 1996 of £2,343 million, or £208 per hectare.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] A 2005 analysis of these costs in the US concluded that cropland imposes approximately $5 to $16 billion ($30 to $96 per hectare), while livestock production imposes $714 million.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Both studies, which focused solely on the fiscal impacts, concluded that more should be done to internalize external costs.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Neither included subsidies in their analysis, but they noted that subsidies also influence the cost of agriculture to society.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agriculture seeks to increase yield and to reduce costs, often employing measures that cut biodiversity to very low levels.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Yield increases with inputs such as fertilizers and removal of pathogens, predators, and competitors (such as weeds).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Costs decrease with increasing scale of farm units, such as making fields larger; this means removing hedges, ditches and other areas of habitat.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Pesticides kill insects, plants and fungi.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Effective yields fall with on-farm losses, which may be caused by poor production practices during harvesting, handling, and storage.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The environmental effects of climate change show that research on pests and diseases that do not generally afflict areas is essential.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] In 2021, farmers discovered stem rust on wheat in the Champagne area of France, a disease that had previously only occurred in Morocco for 20 to 30 years.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Because of climate change, insects that used to die off over the winter are now alive and multiplying.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] A senior UN official, Henning Steinfeld, said that "Livestock are one of the most significant contributors to today's most serious environmental problems".
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Livestock production occupies 70% of all land used for agriculture, or 30% of the land surface of the planet.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] It is one of the largest sources of greenhouse gases, responsible for 18% of the world's greenhouse gas emissions as measured in CO2 equivalents.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] By comparison, all transportation emits 13.5% of the CO2.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] (This comparison later turned out to be an apples-and-oranges analogy.) It produces 65% of human-related nitrous oxide (which has 296 times the global warming potential of CO2) and 37% of all human-induced methane (which is 23 times as warming as CO2.) It also generates 64% of the ammonia emission.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Livestock expansion is cited as a key factor driving deforestation; in the Amazon basin 70% of previously forested area is now occupied by pastures and the remainder used for feed crops.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Through deforestation and land degradation, livestock is also driving reductions in biodiversity.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] A well documented phenomenon is woody plant encroachment, caused by overgrazing in rangelands.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Land transformation, the use of land to yield goods and services, is the most substantial way humans alter the Earth's ecosystems, and is the driving force causing biodiversity loss.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Estimates of the amount of land transformed by humans vary from 39 to 50%.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] It is estimated that 24% of land globally experiences land degradation, a long-term decline in ecosystem function and productivity, with cropland being disproportionately affected.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Land management is the driving factor behind degradation; 1.5 billion people rely upon the degrading land.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Degradation can be through deforestation, desertification, soil erosion, mineral depletion, acidification, or salinization.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] In 2021, the global agricultural land area was 4.79 billion hectares (ha), down 2 percent, or 0.09 billion ha compared with 2000.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Between 2000 and 2021, roughly two-thirds of agricultural land were used for permanent meadows and pastures (3.21 billion ha in 2021), which declined by 5 percent (0.17 billion ha).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] One-third of the total agricultural land was cropland (1.58 billion ha in 2021), which increased by 6 percent (0.09 billion ha).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., total agricultural land use is estimated to be 56%, and including grazing, animal agriculture constitutes around 80% of agricultural land.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Eutrophication, excessive nutrient enrichment in aquatic ecosystems resulting in algal blooms and anoxia, leads to fish kills, loss of biodiversity, and renders water unfit for drinking and other industrial uses.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Excessive fertilization and manure application to cropland, as well as high livestock stocking densities cause nutrient (mainly nitrogen and phosphorus) runoff and leaching from agricultural land.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] These nutrients are major nonpoint pollutants contributing to eutrophication of aquatic ecosystems and pollution of groundwater, with harmful effects on human populations.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Fertilizers also reduce terrestrial biodiversity by increasing competition for light, favoring those species that are able to benefit from the added nutrients.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agriculture simultaneously is facing growing freshwater demand and precipitation anomalies (droughts, floods, and extreme rainfall and weather events) on rainfed areas fields and grazing lands.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for 70 percent of withdrawals of freshwater resources, and an estimated 41 percent of current global irrigation water use occurs at the expense of environmental flow requirements.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., agriculture accounts for about 80% of total water consumption, with animal agriculture making up half of agricultural consumption (around 40%).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] It is long known that aquifers in areas as diverse as northern China, the Upper Ganges and the western US are being depleted, and new research extends these problems to aquifers in Iran, Mexico and Saudi Arabia.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Increasing pressure is being placed on water resources by industry and urban areas, meaning that water scarcity is increasing and agriculture is facing the challenge of producing more food for the world's growing population with reduced water resources.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] While industrial withdrawals have declined in the past few decades and municipal withdrawals have increased only marginally since 2010, agricultural withdrawals have continued to grow at an ever faster pace.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agricultural water usage can also cause major environmental problems, including the destruction of natural wetlands, the spread of water-borne diseases, and land degradation through salinization and waterlogging, when irrigation is performed incorrectly.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Pesticide use has increased since 1950 to 2.5 million short tons annually worldwide, yet crop loss from pests has remained relatively constant.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The World Health Organization estimated in 1992 that three million pesticide poisonings occur annually, causing 220,000 deaths.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Pesticides select for pesticide resistance in the pest population, leading to a condition termed the "pesticide treadmill" in which pest resistance warrants the development of a new pesticide.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] An alternative argument is that the way to "save the environment" and prevent famine is by using pesticides and intensive high yield farming, a view exemplified by a quote heading the Center for Global Food Issues website: 'Growing more per acre leaves more land for nature'.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] However, critics argue that a trade-off between the environment and a need for food is not inevitable, and that pesticides can replace good agronomic practices such as crop rotation.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The Push–pull agricultural pest management technique involves intercropping, using plant aromas to repel pests from crops (push) and to lure them to a place from which they can then be removed (pull).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agriculture contributes towards climate change through greenhouse gas emissions and by the conversion of non-agricultural land such as forests into agricultural land.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The agriculture, forestry and land use sector contribute between 13% and 21% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Emissions of nitrous oxide, methane make up over half of total greenhouse gas emission from agriculture.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Animal husbandry is a major source of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Approximately 57% of global GHG emissions from the production of food are from the production of animal-based food while plant-based foods contribute 29% and the remaining 14% is for other utilizations.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Farmland management and land-use change represented major shares of total emissions (38% and 29%, respectively), whereas rice and beef were the largest contributing plant- and animal-based commodities (12% and 25%, respectively).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] South and Southeast Asia and South America were the largest emitters of production-based GHGs.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Climate change put significant part of crops in danger already at 1.5 degrees of warming.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] While in North America, Europe and central Asia the share of endangered crops is relatively little at this level of warming, in the Middle east and North Africa region for example, close to 50% of cropland is in danger.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] With further temperature rise the risk increase in all regions, in some more, in some less.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Globally the cropland area in safe climatic zone decrease for all the major crop groups as warming exceed 1.5 degrees.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Current farming methods have resulted in over-stretched water resources, high levels of erosion and reduced soil fertility.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] There is not enough water to continue farming using current practices; therefore how water, land, and ecosystem resources are used to boost crop yields must be reconsidered.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] A solution would be to give value to ecosystems, recognizing environmental and livelihood tradeoffs, and balancing the rights of a variety of users and interests.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Inequities that result when such measures are adopted would need to be addressed, such as the reallocation of water from poor to rich, the clearing of land to make way for more productive farmland, or the preservation of a wetland system that limits fishing rights.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Technological advancements help provide farmers with tools and resources to make farming more sustainable.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Technology permits innovations like conservation tillage, a farming process which helps prevent land loss to erosion, reduces water pollution, and enhances carbon sequestration.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agricultural automation can help address some of the challenges associated with climate change and thus facilitate adaptation efforts.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] For example, the application of digital automation technologies (e.g. in precision agriculture) can improve resource-use efficiency in conditions which are increasingly constrained for agricultural producers.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Moreover, when applied to sensing and early warning, they can help address the uncertainty and unpredictability of weather conditions associated with accelerating climate change.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Other potential sustainable practices include conservation agriculture, agroforestry, improved grazing, avoided grassland conversion, and biochar.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Current mono-crop farming practices in the United States preclude widespread adoption of sustainable practices, such as 2–3 crop rotations that incorporate grass or hay with annual crops, unless negative emission goals such as soil carbon sequestration become policy.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The food demand of Earth's projected population, with current climate change predictions, could be satisfied by improvement of agricultural methods, expansion of agricultural areas, and a sustainability-oriented consumer mindset.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Since the 1940s, agricultural productivity has increased dramatically, due largely to the increased use of energy-intensive mechanization, fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The vast majority of this energy input comes from fossil fuel sources.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Between the 1960s and the 1980s, the Green Revolution transformed agriculture around the globe, with world grain production increasing significantly (between 70% and 390% for wheat and 60% to 150% for rice, depending on geographic area) as world population doubled.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Heavy reliance on petrochemicals has raised concerns that oil shortages could increase costs and reduce agricultural output.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Industrialized agriculture depends on fossil fuels in two fundamental ways: direct consumption on the farm and manufacture of inputs used on the farm.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Direct consumption includes the use of lubricants and fuels to operate farm vehicles and machinery.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Indirect consumption includes the manufacture of fertilizers, pesticides, and farm machinery.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] In particular, the production of nitrogen fertilizer can account for over half of agricultural energy usage.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Together, direct and indirect consumption by US farms accounts for about 2% of the nation's energy use.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Direct and indirect energy consumption by US farms peaked in 1979, and has since gradually declined.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Food systems encompass not just agriculture but off-farm processing, packaging, transporting, marketing, consumption, and disposal of food and food-related items.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for less than one-fifth of food system energy use in the US.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Plastic products are used extensively in agriculture, including to increase crop yields and improve the efficiency of water and agrichemical use.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] "Agriplastic" products include films to cover greenhouses and tunnels, mulch to cover soil (e.g. to suppress weeds, conserve water, increase soil temperature and aid fertilizer application), shade cloth, pesticide containers, seedling trays, protective mesh and irrigation tubing.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The polymers most commonly used in these products are low-density polyethylene (LPDE), linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE), polypropylene (PP) and polyvinyl chloride (PVC).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The total amount of plastics used in agriculture is difficult to quantify.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] A 2012 study reported that almost 6.5 million tonnes per year were consumed globally while a later study estimated that global demand in 2015 was between 7.3 million and 9 million tonnes.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Widespread use of plastic mulch and lack of systematic collection and management have led to the generation of large amounts of mulch residue.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Weathering and degradation eventually cause the mulch to fragment.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] These fragments and larger pieces of plastic accumulate in soil.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Mulch residue has been measured at levels of 50 to 260 kg per hectare in topsoil in areas where mulch use dates back more than 10 years, which confirms that mulching is a major source of both microplastic and macroplastic soil contamination.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agricultural plastics, especially plastic films, are not easy to recycle because of high contamination levels (up to 40–50% by weight contamination by pesticides, fertilizers, soil and debris, moist vegetation, silage juice water, and UV stabilizers) and collection difficulties .
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Therefore, they are often buried or abandoned in fields and watercourses or burned.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] These disposal practices lead to soil degradation and can result in contamination of soils and leakage of microplastics into the marine environment as a result of precipitation run-off and tidal washing.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] In addition, additives in residual plastic film (such as UV and thermal stabilizers) may have deleterious effects on crop growth, soil structure, nutrient transport and salt levels.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] There is a risk that plastic mulch will deteriorate soil quality, deplete soil organic matter stocks, increase soil water repellence and emit greenhouse gases.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Microplastics released through fragmentation of agricultural plastics can absorb and concentrate contaminants capable of being passed up the trophic chain.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agricultural economics is economics as it relates to the "production, distribution and consumption of [agricultural] goods and services".
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Combining agricultural production with general theories of marketing and business as a discipline of study began in the late 1800s, and grew significantly through the 20th century.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] In the United States, and elsewhere, food costs attributed to food processing, distribution, and agricultural marketing, sometimes referred to as the value chain, have risen while the costs attributed to farming have declined.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] This is related to the greater efficiency of farming, combined with the increased level of value addition (e.g. more highly processed products) provided by the supply chain.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Market concentration has increased in the sector as well, and although the total effect of the increased market concentration is likely increased efficiency, the changes redistribute economic surplus from producers (farmers) and consumers, and may have negative implications for rural communities.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] National government policies, such as taxation, subsidies, tariffs and others, can significantly change the economic marketplace for agricultural products.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Since at least the 1960s, a combination of trade restrictions, exchange rate policies and subsidies have affected farmers in both the developing and the developed world.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] In the 1980s, non-subsidized farmers in developing countries experienced adverse effects from national policies that created artificially low global prices for farm products.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Between the mid-1980s and the early 2000s, several international agreements limited agricultural tariffs, subsidies and other trade restrictions.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] However, as of 2009, there was still a significant amount of policy-driven distortion in global agricultural product prices.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The three agricultural products with the most trade distortion were sugar, milk and rice, mainly due to taxation.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Among the oilseeds, sesame had the most taxation, but overall, feed grains and oilseeds had much lower levels of taxation than livestock products.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Since the 1980s, policy-driven distortions have decreases more among livestock products than crops during the worldwide reforms in agricultural policy.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Despite this progress, certain crops, such as cotton, still see subsidies in developed countries artificially deflating global prices, causing hardship in developing countries with non-subsidized farmers.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Unprocessed commodities such as corn, soybeans, and cattle are generally graded to indicate quality, affecting the price the producer receives.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Commodities are generally reported by production quantities, such as volume, number or weight.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agricultural science is a broad multidisciplinary field of biology that encompasses the parts of exact, natural, economic and social sciences used in the practice and understanding of agriculture.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The scientific study of agriculture began in the 18th century, when Johann Friedrich Mayer conducted experiments on the use of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulphate) as a fertilizer.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Research became more systematic when in 1843, John Lawes and Henry Gilbert began a set of long-term agronomy field experiments at Rothamsted Research Station in England; some of them, such as the Park Grass Experiment, are still running.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] In America, the Hatch Act of 1887 provided funding for what it was the first to call "agricultural science", driven by farmers' interest in fertilizers.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy is the set of government decisions and actions relating to domestic agriculture and imports of foreign agricultural products.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Governments usually implement agricultural policies with the goal of achieving a specific outcome in the domestic agricultural product markets.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy can also touch on food quality, ensuring that the food supply is of a consistent and known quality, food security, ensuring that the food supply meets the population's needs, and conservation.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Policy programs can range from financial programs, such as subsidies, to encouraging producers to enroll in voluntary quality assurance programs.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] A 2021 report finds that globally, support to agricultural producers accounts for almost US$540 billion a year.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] This amounts to 15 percent of total agricultural production value, and is heavily biased towards measures that are leading to inefficiency, as well as are unequally distributed and harmful for the environment and human health.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Crop use in animal agriculture accounts for one form of inefficiency.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Animal agriculture's estimated land use to produce one kilocalorie or gram of protein is 50 to 100 times that of plant-based alternatives.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Furthermore, the larger the livestock, the lower the energy efficiency (kilocalories obtained relative to kilocalories the animal consumes).
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] For instance, beef's energy efficiency is estimated to be 2%.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] There are many influences on the creation of agricultural policy, including consumers, agribusiness, trade lobbies and other groups.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Agribusiness interests hold a large amount of influence over policy making, in the form of lobbying and campaign contributions.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Political action groups, including those interested in environmental issues and labor unions, also provide influence, as do lobbying organizations representing individual agricultural commodities.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) leads international efforts to defeat hunger and provides a forum for the negotiation of global agricultural regulations and agreements.
[src:eppo-code/agriculture-p02] Samuel Jutzi, director of FAO's animal production and health division, states that lobbying by large corporations has stopped reforms that would improve human health and the environment.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Like all animals, humans carry vast numbers (approximately 1013 to 1014) of bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Most are in the gut, though there are many on the skin.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Most of the bacteria in and on the body are harmless or rendered so by the protective effects of the immune system, and many are beneficial, particularly the ones in the gut.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] However, several species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy, tuberculosis, tetanus and bubonic plague.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are also used in farming, making antibiotic resistance a growing problem.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Once regarded as plants constituting the class *Schizomycetes* ("fission fungi"), bacteria are now classified as prokaryotes.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Unlike cells of animals and other eukaryotes, bacterial cells contain circular chromosomes, do not contain a nucleus and rarely harbour membrane-bound organelles.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Although the term *bacteria* traditionally included all prokaryotes, the scientific classification changed after the discovery in the 1990s that prokaryotes consist of two very different groups of organisms that evolved from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] These evolutionary domains are called Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Unlike Archaea, bacteria contain ester-linked lipids in the cell membrane, possess elongation factors that are resistant to ADP-ribosylation by diphtheria toxin, use formylmethionine in protein synthesis initiation, and have numerous genetic differences, including a different 16S rRNA.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The word was first used to refer to bacteria in 1828.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Although an estimated 43,000 species of bacteria have been named, most of them have never been studied.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In fact, just 10 bacterial species account for half of all publications, whereas nearly 75% of all named bacteria have no academic research devoted to them.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The best-studied species, *Escherichia coli*, has more than 300,000 studies published on it, but many of these papers likely use it only as a cloning vehicle to study other species, without providing any insight into its own biology.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] 90% of scientific studies on bacteria focus on less than 1% of species, mostly pathogenic bacteria relevant to human health.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] While *E. coli* is probably the best-studied bacterium, a quarter of its 4000 genes are poorly studied or remain uncharacterized.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria with minimal genomes (< 600 genes, e.g.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] *Mycoplasma*) usually have a large fraction of their genes functionally characterized, given that most of them are essential and conserved in many other species.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The ancestors of bacteria were unicellular microorganisms that were the first forms of life to appear on Earth, about 4 billion years ago.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] For about 3 billion years, most organisms were microscopic, and bacteria and archaea were the dominant forms of life.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Although bacterial fossils exist, such as stromatolites, their lack of distinctive morphology prevents them from being used to examine the history of bacterial evolution, or to date the time of origin of a particular bacterial species.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] However, gene sequences can be used to reconstruct the bacterial phylogeny, and these studies indicate that bacteria diverged first from the archaeal/eukaryotic lineage.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of bacteria and archaea was probably a hyperthermophile that lived about 2.5 billion–3.2 billion years ago.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The earliest life on land may have been bacteria some 3.22 billion years ago.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria were also involved in the second great evolutionary divergence, that of the archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Here, eukaryotes resulted from the entering of ancient bacteria into endosymbiotic associations with the ancestors of eukaryotic cells, which were themselves possibly related to the Archaea.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This involved the engulfment by proto-eukaryotic cells of alphaproteobacterial symbionts to form either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes, which are still found in all known Eukarya (sometimes in highly reduced form, e.g. in species of amitochondrial protozoa).
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Later, some eukaryotes that already contained mitochondria also engulfed cyanobacteria-like organisms, leading to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria are ubiquitous, living in every possible habitat on the planet including soil, underwater, deep in Earth's crust and even such extreme environments as acidic hot springs and radioactive waste.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] There are thought to be approximately 2×1030 bacteria on Earth, forming a biomass that is only exceeded by plants.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] They are abundant in lakes and oceans, in arctic ice, and geothermal springs where they provide the nutrients needed to sustain life by converting dissolved compounds, such as hydrogen sulphide and methane, to energy.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Most do not cause diseases, are beneficial to their environments, and are essential for life.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The soil is a rich source of bacteria and a few grams contain around a thousand million of them.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] They are all essential to soil ecology, breaking down toxic waste and recycling nutrients.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] They are even found in the atmosphere and one cubic metre of air holds around one hundred million bacterial cells.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The oceans and seas harbour around 3 × 1026 bacteria which provide up to 50% of the oxygen humans breathe.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Only around 2% of bacterial species have been fully studied.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria display a wide diversity of shapes and sizes.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cells are about one-tenth the size of eukaryotic cells and are typically 0.5–5.0 micrometres in length.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] However, a few species are visible to the unaided eye—for example, *Thiomargarita namibiensis* is up to half a millimetre long, *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* reaches 0.7 mm, and *Thiomargarita magnifica* can reach even 2 cm in length, which is 50 times larger than other known bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Among the smallest bacteria are members of the genus *Mycoplasma*, which measure only 0.3 micrometres, as small as the largest viruses.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria may be even smaller, but these ultramicrobacteria are not well-studied.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species are either spherical, called *cocci* (*singular coccus*, from Greek *kókkos*, grain, seed), or rod-shaped, called *bacilli* (*sing*. bacillus, from Latin *baculus*, stick).
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, called *vibrio*, are shaped like slightly curved rods or comma-shaped; others can be spiral-shaped, called *spirilla*, or tightly coiled, called *spirochaetes*.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] A small number of other unusual shapes have been described, such as star-shaped bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This wide variety of shapes is determined by the bacterial cell wall and cytoskeleton and is important because it can influence the ability of bacteria to acquire nutrients, attach to surfaces, swim through liquids and escape predators.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species exist as single cells; others associate in characteristic patterns: *Neisseria* forms diploids (pairs), streptococci form chains, and staphylococci group together in "bunch of grapes" clusters.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can also group to form larger multicellular structures, such as the elongated filaments of *Actinomycetota* species, the aggregates of *Myxobacteria* species, and the complex hyphae of *Streptomyces* species.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] These multicellular structures are often only seen in certain conditions.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] For example, when starved of amino acids, myxobacteria detect surrounding cells in a process known as quorum sensing, migrate towards each other, and aggregate to form fruiting bodies up to 500 micrometres long and containing approximately 100,000 bacterial cells.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In these fruiting bodies, the bacteria perform separate tasks; for example, about one in ten cells migrate to the top of a fruiting body and differentiate into a specialised dormant state called a myxospore, which is more resistant to drying and other adverse environmental conditions.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often attach to surfaces and form dense aggregations called biofilms and larger formations known as microbial mats.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] These biofilms and mats can range from a few micrometres in thickness to up to half a metre in depth, and may contain multiple species of bacteria, protists and archaea.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria living in biofilms display a complex arrangement of cells and extracellular components, forming secondary structures, such as microcolonies, through which there are networks of channels to enable better diffusion of nutrients.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In natural environments, such as soil or the surfaces of plants, the majority of bacteria are bound to surfaces in biofilms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Biofilms are also important in medicine, as these structures are often present during chronic bacterial infections or in infections of implanted medical devices, and bacteria protected within biofilms are much harder to kill than individual isolated bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The bacterial cell is surrounded by a cell membrane, which is made primarily of phospholipids.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This membrane encloses the contents of the cell and acts as a barrier to hold nutrients, proteins and other essential components within the cell.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Unlike eukaryotic cells, bacteria usually lack large membrane-bound structures in their cytoplasm such as a nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts and the other organelles present in eukaryotic cells.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] However, some bacteria have protein-bound organelles in the cytoplasm which compartmentalise aspects of bacterial metabolism, such as the carboxysome.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Additionally, bacteria have a multi-component cytoskeleton to control the localisation of proteins and nucleic acids within the cell, and to manage the process of cell division.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Many important biochemical reactions, such as energy generation, occur due to differences in concentration of molecules across membranes, creating a electrochemical potential analogous to a battery.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The general lack of internal membranes in bacteria means these reactions, such as electron transport, occur across the cell membrane between the cytoplasm and the outside of the cell or periplasm.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] However, in many photosynthetic bacteria, the plasma membrane is highly folded and fills most of the cell with layers of light-gathering membrane.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] These light-gathering complexes may even form lipid-enclosed structures called chlorosomes in green sulfur bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria do not have a membrane-bound nucleus, and their genetic material is typically a single circular bacterial chromosome of DNA located in the cytoplasm in an irregularly shaped body called the nucleoid.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The nucleoid contains the chromosome with its associated proteins and RNA.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Like all other organisms, bacteria contain ribosomes for the production of proteins, but the structure of the bacterial ribosome is different from that of eukaryotes and archaea.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Its translation process is also different.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria produce intracellular nutrient storage granules, such as glycogen, polyphosphate, sulfur or polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria such as the photosynthetic cyanobacteria, produce internal gas vacuoles, which they use to regulate their buoyancy, allowing them to move up or down into water layers with different light intensities and nutrient levels.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the cell wall.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by peptides containing D-amino acids.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi, which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, and the antibiotic penicillin (produced by a fungus called *Penicillium*) is able to kill bacteria by inhibiting a step in the synthesis of peptidoglycan.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, that classify bacteria into Gram-positive bacteria and Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a long-standing test for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have the Gram-negative cell wall, and only members of the *Bacillota* group and actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C Gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative Gram-positive arrangement.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] These differences in structure can produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility; for instance, vancomycin can kill only Gram-positive bacteria and is ineffective against Gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria have cell wall structures that are neither classically Gram-positive or Gram-negative.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This includes clinically important bacteria such as mycobacteria which have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall like a Gram-positive bacterium, but also a second outer layer of lipids.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In many bacteria, an S-layer of rigidly arrayed protein molecules covers the outside of the cell.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This layer provides chemical and physical protection for the cell surface and can act as a macromolecular diffusion barrier.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] S-layers have diverse functions and are known to act as virulence factors in *Campylobacter* species and contain surface enzymes in *Bacillus stearothermophilus*.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Flagella are rigid protein structures, about 20 nanometres in diameter and up to 20 micrometres in length, that are used for motility.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Flagella are driven by the energy released by the transfer of ions down an electrochemical gradient across the cell membrane.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are fine filaments of protein, usually 2–10 nanometres in diameter and up to several micrometres in length.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] They are distributed over the surface of the cell, and resemble fine hairs when seen under the electron microscope.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae are believed to be involved in attachment to solid surfaces or to other cells, and are essential for the virulence of some bacterial pathogens.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Pili (*sing*. pilus) are cellular appendages, slightly larger than fimbriae, that can transfer genetic material between bacterial cells in a process called conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or sex pili (see bacterial genetics, below).
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] They can also generate movement where they are called type IV pili.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Glycocalyx is produced by many bacteria to surround their cells, and varies in structural complexity: ranging from a disorganised slime layer of extracellular polymeric substances to a highly structured capsule.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] These structures can protect cells from engulfment by eukaryotic cells such as macrophages (part of the human immune system).
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] They can also act as antigens and be involved in cell recognition, as well as aiding attachment to surfaces and the formation of biofilms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The assembly of these extracellular structures is dependent on bacterial secretion systems.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] These transfer proteins from the cytoplasm into the periplasm or into the environment around the cell.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Many types of secretion systems are known and these structures are often essential for the virulence of pathogens, so are intensively studied.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some genera of Gram-positive bacteria, such as *Bacillus*, *Clostridium*, *Sporohalobacter*, *Anaerobacter*, and *Heliobacterium*, can form highly resistant, dormant structures called *endospores*.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Endospores develop within the cytoplasm of the cell; generally, a single endospore develops in each cell.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Each endospore contains a core of DNA and ribosomes surrounded by a cortex layer and protected by a multilayer rigid coat composed of peptidoglycan and a variety of proteins.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Endospores show no detectable metabolism and can survive extreme physical and chemical stresses, such as high levels of UV light, gamma radiation, detergents, disinfectants, heat, freezing, pressure, and desiccation.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In this dormant state, these organisms may remain viable for millions of years.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Endospores even allow bacteria to survive exposure to the vacuum and radiation of outer space, leading to the possibility that bacteria could be distributed throughout the universe by space dust, meteoroids, asteroids, comets, planetoids, or directed panspermia.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] *Clostridioides difficile* infection, a common problem in healthcare settings, is caused by spore-forming bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria exhibit an extremely wide variety of metabolic types.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The distribution of metabolic traits within a group of bacteria has traditionally been used to define their taxonomy, but these traits often do not correspond with modern genetic classifications.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolism is classified into nutritional groups on the basis of three major criteria: the source of energy, the electron donors used, and the source of carbon used for growth.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Phototrophic bacteria derive energy from light using photosynthesis, while chemotrophic bacteria breaking down chemical compounds through oxidation, driving metabolism by transferring electrons from a given electron donor to a terminal electron acceptor in a redox reaction.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Chemotrophs are further divided by the types of compounds they use to transfer electrons.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria that derive electrons from inorganic compounds such as hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or ammonia are called lithotrophs, while those that use organic compounds are called organotrophs.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Still, more specifically, aerobic organisms use oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor, while anaerobic organisms use other compounds such as nitrate, sulfate, or carbon dioxide.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria, called heterotrophs, derive their carbon from other organic carbon.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Others, such as cyanobacteria and some purple bacteria, are autotrophic, meaning they obtain cellular carbon by fixing carbon dioxide.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In unusual circumstances, the gas methane can be used by methanotrophic bacteria as both a source of electrons and a substrate for carbon anabolism.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In many ways, bacterial metabolism provides traits that are useful for ecological stability and for human society.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] For example, diazotrophs have the ability to fix nitrogen gas using the enzyme nitrogenase.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This trait, which can be found in bacteria of most metabolic types listed above, leads to the ecologically important processes of denitrification, sulfate reduction, and acetogenesis, respectively.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolic processes are important drivers in biological responses to pollution; for example, sulfate-reducing bacteria are largely responsible for the production of the highly toxic forms of mercury (methyl- and dimethylmercury) in the environment.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Nonrespiratory anaerobes use fermentation to generate energy and reducing power, secreting metabolic by-products (such as ethanol in brewing) as waste.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Facultative anaerobes can switch between fermentation and different terminal electron acceptors depending on the environmental conditions in which they find themselves.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Unlike in multicellular organisms, increases in cell size (cell growth) and reproduction by cell division are tightly linked in unicellular organisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria grow to a fixed size and then reproduce through binary fission, a form of asexual reproduction.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Under optimal conditions, bacteria can grow and divide extremely rapidly, and some bacterial populations can double as quickly as every 17 minutes.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In cell division, two identical clone daughter cells are produced.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, while still reproducing asexually, form more complex reproductive structures that help disperse the newly formed daughter cells.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Examples include fruiting body formation by myxobacteria and aerial hyphae formation by *Streptomyces* species, or budding.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Budding involves a cell forming a protrusion that breaks away and produces a daughter cell.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In the laboratory, bacteria are usually grown using solid or liquid media.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Solid growth media, such as agar plates, are used to isolate pure cultures of a bacterial strain.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] However, liquid growth media are used when the measurement of growth or large volumes of cells are required.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Growth in stirred liquid media occurs as an even cell suspension, making the cultures easy to divide and transfer, although isolating single bacteria from liquid media is difficult.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The use of selective media (media with specific nutrients added or deficient, or with antibiotics added) can help identify specific organisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Most laboratory techniques for growing bacteria use high levels of nutrients to produce large amounts of cells cheaply and quickly.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] However, in natural environments, nutrients are limited, meaning that bacteria cannot continue to reproduce indefinitely.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This nutrient limitation has led the evolution of different growth strategies (see r/K selection theory).
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some organisms can grow extremely rapidly when nutrients become available, such as the formation of algal and cyanobacterial blooms that often occur in lakes during the summer.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Other organisms have adaptations to harsh environments, such as the production of multiple antibiotics by *Streptomyces* that inhibit the growth of competing microorganisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In nature, many organisms live in communities (e.g., biofilms) that may allow for increased supply of nutrients and protection from environmental stresses.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] These relationships can be essential for growth of a particular organism or group of organisms (syntrophy).
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] When a population of bacteria first enter a high-nutrient environment that allows growth, the cells need to adapt to their new environment.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The first phase of growth is the lag phase, a period of slow growth when the cells are adapting to the high-nutrient environment and preparing for fast growth.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The lag phase has high biosynthesis rates, as proteins necessary for rapid growth are produced.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The second phase of growth is the logarithmic phase, also known as the exponential phase.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The log phase is marked by rapid exponential growth.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The rate at which cells grow during this phase is known as the *growth rate* (*k*), and the time it takes the cells to double is known as the *generation time* (*g*).
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] During log phase, nutrients are metabolised at maximum speed until one of the nutrients is depleted and starts limiting growth.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The third phase of growth is the *stationary phase* and is caused by depleted nutrients.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The cells reduce their metabolic activity and consume non-essential cellular proteins.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The stationary phase is a transition from rapid growth to a stress response state and there is increased expression of genes involved in DNA repair, antioxidant metabolism and nutrient transport.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The final phase is the death phase where the bacteria run out of nutrients and die.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] There are many exceptions to this; for example, some *Streptomyces* and *Borrelia* species contain a single linear chromosome, while some bacteria including species of *Vibrio* contain more than one chromosome.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria contain plasmids, small extra-chromosomal molecules of DNA that may contain genes for various useful functions such as antibiotic resistance, metabolic capabilities, or various virulence factors.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Whether they have a single chromosome or more than one, almost all bacteria have a haploid genome.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This means that they have only one copy of each gene encoding proteins.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This is in contrast to eukaryotes, which are diploid or polyploid, meaning they have two or more copies of each gene.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This means that unlike humans, who may still be able to create a protein if the gene becomes mutated (since the human genome has an extra copy in each cell), a bacterium will be completely unable to create the protein if its gene incurs an inactivating mutation.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacterial genomes usually encode a few hundred to a few thousand genes.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The genes in bacterial genomes are usually a single continuous stretch of DNA.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Although several different types of introns do exist in bacteria, these are much rarer than in eukaryotes.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria, as asexual organisms, inherit an identical copy of the parent's genome and are clonal.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] However, all bacteria can evolve by selection on changes to their genetic material DNA caused by genetic recombination or mutations.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Mutations arise from errors made during the replication of DNA or from exposure to mutagens.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Mutation rates vary widely among different species of bacteria and even among different clones of a single species of bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Genetic changes in bacterial genomes emerge from either random mutation during replication or "stress-directed mutation", where genes involved in a particular growth-limiting process have an increased mutation rate.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria transfer genetic material between cells.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] First, bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment in a process called transformation.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria can naturally take up DNA from the environment, while others must be chemically altered in order to induce them to take up DNA.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Second, bacteriophages can integrate into the bacterial chromosome, introducing foreign DNA in a process known as transduction.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Many types of bacteriophage exist; some infect and lyse their host bacteria, while others insert into the bacterial chromosome.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Third, bacteria can transfer genetic material through direct cell contact via conjugation.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In such cases, gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria are motile (able to move themselves) and do so using a variety of mechanisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The best studied of these are flagella, long filaments that are turned by a motor at the base to generate propeller-like movement.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The bacterial flagellum is made of about 20 proteins, with approximately another 30 proteins required for its regulation and assembly.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The flagellum is a rotating structure driven by a reversible motor at the base that uses the electrochemical gradient across the membrane for power.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can use flagella in different ways to generate different kinds of movement.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria (such as *E. coli*) have two distinct modes of movement: forward movement (swimming) and tumbling.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The tumbling allows them to reorient and makes their movement a three-dimensional random walk.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The flagella of a group of bacteria, the spirochaetes, are found between two membranes in the periplasmic space.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] They have a distinctive helical body that twists about as it moves.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Two other types of bacterial motion are called twitching motility that relies on a structure called the type IV pilus, and gliding motility, that uses other mechanisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In twitching motility, the rod-like pilus extends out from the cell, binds some substrate, and then retracts, pulling the cell forward.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Motile bacteria are attracted or repelled by certain stimuli in behaviours called *taxes*: these include chemotaxis, phototaxis, energy taxis, and magnetotaxis.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] In one peculiar group, the myxobacteria, individual bacteria move together to form waves of cells that then differentiate to form fruiting bodies containing spores.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The myxobacteria move only when on solid surfaces, unlike *E. coli*, which is motile in liquid or solid media.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Several *Listeria* and *Shigella* species move inside host cells by usurping the cytoskeleton, which is normally used to move organelles inside the cell.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] By promoting actin polymerisation at one pole of their cells, they can form a kind of tail that pushes them through the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] A few bacteria have chemical systems that generate light.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This bioluminescence often occurs in bacteria that live in association with fish, and the light probably serves to attract fish or other large animals.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often function as multicellular aggregates known as biofilms, exchanging a variety of molecular signals for intercell communication and engaging in coordinated multicellular behaviour.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The communal benefits of multicellular cooperation include a cellular division of labour, accessing resources that cannot effectively be used by single cells, collectively defending against antagonists, and optimising population survival by differentiating into distinct cell types.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] For example, bacteria in biofilms can have more than five hundred times the increased resistance to antibacterial agents than individual "planktonic" bacteria of the same species.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] One type of intercellular communication by a molecular signal is called quorum sensing.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing determines whether the local population is dense enough to support investment in processes that are only successful if large numbers of similar organisms behave similarly, such as excreting digestive enzymes or emitting light.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing enables bacteria to coordinate gene expression and to produce, release, and detect autoinducers or pheromones that accumulate with the growth in cell population.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Classification seeks to describe the diversity of bacterial species by naming and grouping organisms based on similarities.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can be classified on the basis of cell structure, cellular metabolism or on differences in cell components, such as DNA, fatty acids, pigments, antigens and quinones.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] While these schemes allowed the identification and classification of **bacterial strains**, it was unclear whether these differences represented variation between distinct species or between strains of the same species.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This uncertainty was due to the lack of distinctive structures in most bacteria, as well as lateral gene transfer between unrelated species.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Due to lateral gene transfer, some closely related bacteria can have very different morphologies and metabolisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Classification of bacteria is determined by publication in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology, and Bergey's Manual of Systematic Bacteriology.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The International Committee on Systematic Bacteriology (ICSB) maintains international rules for the naming of bacteria and taxonomic categories and for the ranking of them in the International Code of Nomenclature of Bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Historically, bacteria were considered a part of the Plantae, the plant kingdom, and were called "Schizomycetes" (fission-fungi).
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] For this reason, collective bacteria and other microorganisms in a host are often called "flora".
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The term "bacteria" was traditionally applied to all microscopic, single-cell prokaryotes.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] However, molecular systematics showed prokaryotic life to consist of two separate domains, originally called Eubacteria and Archaebacteria, but now called Bacteria and Archaea that evolved independently from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The archaea and eukaryotes are more closely related to each other than either is to the bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] These two domains, along with Eukarya, are the basis of the three-domain system, which is currently the most widely used classification system in microbiology.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] However, due to the relatively recent introduction of molecular systematics and a rapid increase in the number of genome sequences that are available, bacterial classification remains a changing and expanding field.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] For example, Cavalier-Smith argued that the Archaea and Eukaryotes evolved from Gram-positive bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The identification of bacteria in the laboratory is particularly relevant in medicine, where the correct treatment is determined by the bacterial species causing an infection.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Consequently, the need to identify human pathogens was a major impetus for the development of techniques to identify bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Once a pathogenic organism has been isolated, it can be further characterised by its morphology, growth patterns (such as aerobic or anaerobic growth), patterns of hemolysis, and staining.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The *Gram stain*, developed in 1884 by Hans Christian Gram, characterises bacteria based on the structural characteristics of their cell walls.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The thick layers of peptidoglycan in the "Gram-positive" cell wall stain purple, while the thin "Gram-negative" cell wall appears pink.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] By combining morphology and Gram-staining, most bacteria can be classified as belonging to one of four groups (Gram-positive cocci, Gram-positive bacilli, Gram-negative cocci and Gram-negative bacilli).
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Some organisms are best identified by stains other than the Gram stain, particularly mycobacteria or *Nocardia*, which show acid fastness on Ziehl–Neelsen or similar stains.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Culture techniques are designed to promote the growth and identify particular bacteria while restricting the growth of the other bacteria in the sample.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Often these techniques are designed for specific specimens; for example, a sputum sample will be treated to identify organisms that cause pneumonia, while stool specimens are cultured on selective media to identify organisms that cause diarrhea while preventing growth of non-pathogenic bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Specimens that are normally sterile, such as blood, urine or spinal fluid, are cultured under conditions designed to grow all possible organisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Other organisms may need to be identified by their growth in special media, or by other techniques, such as serology.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] As with bacterial classification, identification of bacteria is increasingly using molecular methods, and mass spectroscopy.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have not been characterised and there are many species that cannot be grown in the laboratory.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Diagnostics using DNA-based tools, such as polymerase chain reaction, are increasingly popular due to their specificity and speed, compared to culture-based methods.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] These methods also allow the detection and identification of "viable but nonculturable" cells that are metabolically active but non-dividing.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] The main way to characterize and classify these bacteria is to isolate their DNA from environmental samples and mass-sequence them.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] This approach has identified thousands, if not millions of candidate species.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p01] Based on some estimates, more than 43,000 species of bacteria have been described, but attempts to estimate the true number of bacterial diversity have ranged from 107 to 109 total species—and even these diverse estimates may be off by many orders of magnitude.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Despite their apparent simplicity, bacteria can form complex associations with other organisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] These symbiotic associations can be divided into parasitism, mutualism and commensalism.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] The word "commensalism" is derived from the word "commensal", meaning "eating at the same table" and all plants and animals are colonised by commensal bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] In humans and other animals, trillions of them live on the skin, the airways, the gut and other orifices.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Referred to as "normal flora", or "commensals", these bacteria usually cause no harm but may occasionally invade other sites of the body and cause infection.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] *Escherichia coli* is a commensal in the human gut but can cause urinary tract infections.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Similarly, streptococci, which are part of the normal flora of the human mouth, can cause heart disease.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Some species of bacteria kill and then consume other microorganisms; these species are called *predatory bacteria*.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] These include organisms such as *Myxococcus xanthus*, which forms swarms of cells that kill and digest any bacteria they encounter.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Other bacterial predators either attach to their prey in order to digest them and absorb nutrients or invade another cell and multiply inside the cytosol.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] These predatory bacteria are thought to have evolved from saprophages that consumed dead microorganisms, through adaptations that allowed them to entrap and kill other organisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Certain bacteria form close spatial associations that are essential for their survival.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] One such mutualistic association, called interspecies hydrogen transfer, occurs between clusters of anaerobic bacteria that consume organic acids, such as butyric acid or propionic acid, and produce hydrogen, and methanogenic archaea that consume hydrogen.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] The bacteria in this association are unable to consume the organic acids as this reaction produces hydrogen that accumulates in their surroundings.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Only the intimate association with the hydrogen-consuming archaea keeps the hydrogen concentration low enough to allow the bacteria to grow.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] In soil, microorganisms that reside in the rhizosphere (a zone that includes the root surface and the soil that adheres to the root after gentle shaking) carry out nitrogen fixation, converting nitrogen gas to nitrogenous compounds.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] This serves to provide an easily absorbable form of nitrogen for many plants, which cannot fix nitrogen themselves.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Many other bacteria are found as symbionts in humans and other organisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] The presence of this gut flora also inhibits the growth of potentially pathogenic bacteria (usually through competitive exclusion) and these beneficial bacteria are consequently sold as probiotic dietary supplements.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Nearly all animal life is dependent on bacteria for survival as only bacteria and some archaea possess the genes and enzymes necessary to synthesise vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, and provide it through the food chain.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Vitamin B12 is a water-soluble vitamin that is involved in the metabolism of every cell of the human body.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] It is a cofactor in DNA synthesis and in both fatty acid and amino acid metabolism.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] It is particularly important in the normal functioning of the nervous system via its role in the synthesis of myelin.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] The body is continually exposed to many species of bacteria, including beneficial commensals, which grow on the skin and mucous membranes, and saprophytes, which grow mainly in the soil and in decaying matter.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] The blood and tissue fluids contain nutrients sufficient to sustain the growth of many bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] The body has defence mechanisms that enable it to resist microbial invasion of its tissues and give it a natural immunity or innate resistance against many microorganisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Unlike some viruses, bacteria evolve relatively slowly so many bacterial diseases also occur in other animals.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] If bacteria form a parasitic association with other organisms, they are classed as pathogens.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] A pathogenic cause for a known medical disease may only be discovered many years later, as was the case with *Helicobacter pylori* and peptic ulcer disease.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Bacterial diseases are also important in agriculture, and bacteria cause leaf spot, fire blight and wilts in plants, as well as Johne's disease, mastitis, salmonella and anthrax in farm animals.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Each species of pathogen has a characteristic spectrum of interactions with its human hosts.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Some organisms, such as *Staphylococcus* or *Streptococcus*, can cause skin infections, pneumonia, meningitis and sepsis, a systemic inflammatory response producing shock, massive vasodilation and death.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Yet these organisms are also part of the normal human flora and usually exist on the skin or in the nose without causing any disease at all.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Other organisms invariably cause disease in humans, such as *Rickettsia*, which are obligate intracellular parasites able to grow and reproduce only within the cells of other organisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] One species of *Rickettsia* causes typhus, while another causes Rocky Mountain spotted fever.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] *Chlamydia*, another phylum of obligate intracellular parasites, contains species that can cause pneumonia or urinary tract infection and may be involved in coronary heart disease.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Some species, such as *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Burkholderia cenocepacia*, and *Mycobacterium avium*, are opportunistic pathogens and cause disease mainly in people who are immunosuppressed or have cystic fibrosis.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Some bacteria produce toxins, which cause diseases.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] These are endotoxins, which come from broken bacterial cells, and exotoxins, which are produced by bacteria and released into the environment.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] The bacterium *Clostridium botulinum* for example, produces a powerful exotoxin that cause respiratory paralysis, and *Salmonellae* produce an endotoxin that causes gastroenteritis.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Some exotoxins can be converted to toxoids, which are used as vaccines to prevent the disease.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Bacterial infections may be treated with antibiotics, which are classified as bacteriocidal if they kill bacteria or bacteriostatic if they just prevent bacterial growth.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] There are many types of antibiotics, and each class inhibits a process that is different in the pathogen from that found in the host.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] An example of how antibiotics produce selective toxicity are chloramphenicol and puromycin, which inhibit the bacterial ribosome, but not the structurally different eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Antibiotics are used both in treating human disease and in intensive farming to promote animal growth, where they may be contributing to the rapid development of antibiotic resistance in bacterial populations.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Infections can be prevented by antiseptic measures such as sterilising the skin prior to piercing it with the needle of a syringe, and by proper care of indwelling catheters.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Surgical and dental instruments are also sterilised to prevent contamination by bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Disinfectants such as bleach are used to kill bacteria or other pathogens on surfaces to prevent contamination and further reduce the risk of infection.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Bacteria, often lactic acid bacteria, such as *Lactobacillus* species and *Lactococcus* species, in combination with yeasts and moulds, have been used for thousands of years in the preparation of fermented foods, such as cheese, pickles, soy sauce, sauerkraut, vinegar, wine, and yogurt.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] The ability of bacteria to degrade a variety of organic compounds is remarkable and has been used in waste processing and bioremediation.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Bacteria capable of digesting the hydrocarbons in petroleum are often used to clean up oil spills.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Fertiliser was added to some of the beaches in Prince William Sound in an attempt to promote the growth of these naturally occurring bacteria after the 1989 *Exxon Valdez* oil spill.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] These efforts were effective on beaches that were not too thickly covered in oil.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Bacteria are also used for the bioremediation of industrial toxic wastes.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] In the chemical industry, bacteria are most important in the production of enantiomerically pure chemicals for use as pharmaceuticals or agrichemicals.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Bacteria can also be used in place of pesticides in biological pest control.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] This commonly involves *Bacillus thuringiensis* (also called BT), a Gram-positive, soil-dwelling bacterium.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Subspecies of this bacteria are used as Lepidopteran-specific insecticides under trade names such as Dipel and Thuricide.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Because of their specificity, these pesticides are regarded as environmentally friendly, with little or no effect on humans, wildlife, pollinators, and most other beneficial insects.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Because of their ability to quickly grow and the relative ease with which they can be manipulated, bacteria are the workhorses for the fields of molecular biology, genetics, and biochemistry.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] By making mutations in bacterial DNA and examining the resulting phenotypes, scientists can determine the function of genes, enzymes, and metabolic pathways in bacteria, then apply this knowledge to more complex organisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] This aim of understanding the biochemistry of a cell reaches its most complex expression in the synthesis of huge amounts of enzyme kinetic and gene expression data into mathematical models of entire organisms.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] This is achievable in some well-studied bacteria, with models of *Escherichia coli* metabolism now being produced and tested.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] This understanding of bacterial metabolism and genetics allows the use of biotechnology to bioengineer bacteria for the production of therapeutic proteins, such as insulin, growth factors, or antibodies.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Because of their importance for research in general, samples of bacterial strains are isolated and preserved in Biological Resource Centres.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] This ensures the availability of the strain to scientists worldwide.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were first observed by the Dutch microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1676, using a single-lens microscope of his own design.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Leeuwenhoek did not recognize bacteria as a distinct category of microorganisms, referring to all microorganisms that he observed, including bacteria, protists, and microscopic animals, as animalcules.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] He published his observations in a series of letters to the Royal Society of London.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were Leeuwenhoek's most remarkable microscopic discovery.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Their size was just at the limit of what his simple lenses could resolve, and, in one of the most striking hiatuses in the history of science, no one else would see them again for over a century.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] His observations also included protozoans, and his findings were looked at again in the light of the more recent findings of cell theory.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg introduced the word "bacterium" in 1828.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] In fact, his *Bacterium* was a genus that contained non-spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria, as opposed to *Bacillus*, a genus of spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria defined by Ehrenberg in 1835.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Louis Pasteur demonstrated in 1859 that the growth of microorganisms causes the fermentation process and that this growth is not due to spontaneous generation (yeasts and molds, commonly associated with fermentation, are not bacteria, but rather fungi).
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Along with his contemporary Robert Koch, Pasteur was an early advocate of the germ theory of disease.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Before them, Ignaz Semmelweis and Joseph Lister had realised the importance of sanitised hands in medical work.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Semmelweis, who in the 1840s formulated his rules for handwashing in the hospital, prior to the advent of germ theory, attributed disease to "decomposing animal organic matter".
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] His ideas were rejected and his book on the topic condemned by the medical community.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] After Lister, however, doctors started sanitising their hands in the 1870s.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Robert Koch, a pioneer in medical microbiology, worked on cholera, anthrax and tuberculosis.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] In his research into tuberculosis, Koch finally proved the germ theory, for which he received a Nobel Prize in 1905.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] In Koch's postulates, he set out criteria to test if an organism is the cause of a disease, and these postulates are still used today.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Ferdinand Cohn is said to be a founder of bacteriology, studying bacteria from 1870.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Cohn was the first to classify bacteria based on their morphology.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Though it was known in the nineteenth century that bacteria are the cause of many diseases, no effective antibacterial treatments were available.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] In 1910, Paul Ehrlich developed the first antibiotic, by changing dyes that selectively stained *Treponema pallidum*—the spirochaete that causes syphilis—into compounds that selectively killed the pathogen.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] Ehrlich, who had been awarded a 1908 Nobel Prize for his work on immunology, pioneered the use of stains to detect and identify bacteria, with his work being the basis of the Gram stain and the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] A major step forward in the study of bacteria came in 1977 when Carl Woese recognised that archaea have a separate line of evolutionary descent from bacteria.
[src:eppo-code/bacteria-p02] This new phylogenetic taxonomy depended on the sequencing of 16S ribosomal RNA and divided prokaryotes into two evolutionary domains, as part of the three-domain system.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] Bayer AG began marketing in the United States soon after the company's inception in Germany.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In the late 19th century, they began to sell their trademark medication, aspirin.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] While the name "aspirin" became synonymous with Bayer for over a quarter of a century, the company's patents and trademarks were seized by the United States Office of Alien Property Custodian in 1917, due to Germany's enemy status in World War I.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] These assets were later auctioned and sold to Sterling Drug.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In 1954, Bayer AG and Monsanto reached an agreement for establishment of a joint venture that was to be called Mobay.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] Louis, Mobay established its headquarters in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania in 1958, moving to a location in Robinson Township in 1960.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] A polyurethanes manufacturing site in New Martinsville, West Virginia began operation in 1955.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In 1964 the United States Department of Justice brought antitrust action against Mobay, resulting in Bayer AG reaching an agreement to purchase Monsanto's share of the company in 1967.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In October 1971 Mobay, along with five other Bayer-owned chemical-related subsidiaries in the United States, merged into a single company called Baychem Chemical Company and headquartered in New York City.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] By 1974 the company relocated to Pittsburgh under the name Mobay Chemical Company.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In that same decade two additional United States companies were acquired and merged into Mobay: Cutter Laboratories in 1974 and Miles Laboratories in 1978.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In 1992 Bayer consolidated its United States operations under the name Miles, and the Mobay name was discontinued.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In 1994, Bayer reacquired full rights to all former Bayer products after they purchased the Winthrop division of over-the-counter drugs from GlaxoSmithKline, and the Miles name was discontinued.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In 2012, Bayer relocated the top United States administrative head to the Bayer HealthCare site in Whippany.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In 2019, Bayer announced the end of it operations at its Pittsburgh site.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] Later that year Bayer agreed to sell its Pittsburgh facilities to Covestro.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] On September 18, 2014, the Board of Directors of Bayer AG announced plans to float the Bayer MaterialScience business on the stock market as a separate entity.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] This transaction was completed in the fall of 2015 with the establishment of Covestro AG.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] Noted over-the-counter Bayer products include Aleve, Bayer Aspirin, Alka-Seltzer, Phillip's Laxatives, Bactine, One-A-Day Vitamins, Flintstone Vitamins, and Midol.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] The company also markets prescription medications, animal medications, and diagnostic and medical testing equipment.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] Aside from the medical arm of the company, Bayer also creates many different chemicals and agricultural products.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In 2018, Bayer purchased the American agricultural product producer Monsanto Co.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] With the purchase, Bayer also took on litigation against its weedkiller product, Roundup, which was subject to thousands of lawsuits, representing nearly 100,000 people, claiming the product caused their cancer.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] While Bayer denied wrongdoing, it did reach a 2020 settlement of $10 billion to eliminate uncertainty and resolve outstanding claims.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] In 1953, Bayer Corporation founded the first of three foundations that were later merged into the Bayer USA Foundation to support philanthropic giving in the United States.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] Foundation grants focus on education and workforce development, and environment and sustainability.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] Making Science Make Sense (MSMS) is a science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) social responsibility program to provide hands-on, inquiry-based educational opportunities in the United States.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] The program focuses on promoting science and scientific principles to students in grades K-20.
[src:eppo-code/bayer-corporation] Astronaut Mae Jemison is the national spokesperson for MSMS.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] In agriculture, pests are kept at bay by mechanical, cultural, chemical and biological means.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Ploughing and cultivation of the soil before sowing mitigate the pest burden, and crop rotation helps to reduce the build-up of a certain pest species.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Concern about environment means limiting the use of pesticides in favour of other methods.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] This can be achieved by monitoring the crop, only applying pesticides when necessary, and by growing varieties and crops which are resistant to pests.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Where possible, biological means are used, encouraging the natural enemies of the pests and introducing suitable predators or parasites.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] In homes and urban environments, the pests are the rodents, birds, insects and other organisms that share the habitat with humans, and that feed on or spoil possessions.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Control of these pests is attempted through exclusion or quarantine, repulsion, physical removal or chemical means.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Alternatively, various methods of biological control can be used including sterilisation programmes.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Pest control is at least as old as agriculture, as there has always been a need to keep crops free from pests.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] As long ago as 3000 BC in Egypt, cats were used to control pests of grain stores such as rodents.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Ferrets were domesticated by 1500 BC in Europe for use as mousers.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Mongooses were introduced into homes to control rodents and snakes, probably by the ancient Egyptians.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The conventional approach was probably the first to be employed, since it is comparatively easy to destroy weeds by burning them or ploughing them under, and to kill larger competing herbivores.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Techniques such as crop rotation, companion planting (also known as intercropping or mixed cropping), and the selective breeding of pest-resistant cultivars have a long history.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Chemical pesticides were first used around 2500 BC, when the Sumerians used sulphur compounds as insecticides.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Modern pest control was stimulated by the spread across the United States of the Colorado potato beetle.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] After much discussion, arsenical compounds were used to control the beetle and the predicted poisoning of the human population did not occur.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] This led the way to a widespread acceptance of insecticides across the continent.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] With the industrialisation and mechanization of agriculture in the 18th and 19th centuries, and the introduction of the insecticides pyrethrum and derris, chemical pest control became widespread.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] In the 20th century, the discovery of several synthetic insecticides, such as DDT, and herbicides boosted this development.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The harmful side effect of pesticides on humans has now resulted in the development of newer approaches, such as the use of biological control to eliminate the ability of pests to reproduce or to modify their behavior to make them less troublesome.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Biological control is first recorded around 300 AD in China, when colonies of weaver ants, *Oecophylla smaragdina*, were intentionally placed in citrus plantations to control beetles and caterpillars.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Also around 4000 BC in China, ducks were used in paddy fields to consume pests, as illustrated in ancient cave art.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] In 1762, an Indian mynah was brought to Mauritius to control locusts, and about the same time, citrus trees in Burma were connected by bamboos to allow ants to pass between them and help control caterpillars.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] In the 1880s, ladybirds were used in citrus plantations in California to control scale insects, and other biological control experiments followed.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The introduction of DDT, a cheap and effective compound, put an effective stop to biological control experiments.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] By the 1960s, problems of resistance to chemicals and damage to the environment began to emerge, and biological control had a renaissance.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Chemical pest control is still the predominant type of pest control today, although a renewed interest in traditional and biological pest control developed towards the end of the 20th century and continues to this day.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Biological pest control is a method of controlling pests such as insects and mites by using other organisms.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] It relies on predation, parasitism, herbivory, parasitody or other natural mechanisms, but typically also involves an active human management role.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Classical biological control involves the introduction of natural enemies of the pest that are bred in the laboratory and released into the environment.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] An alternative approach is to augment the natural enemies that occur in a particular area by releasing more, either in small, repeated batches, or in a single large-scale release.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Ideally, the released organism will breed and survive, and provide long-term control.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Biological control can be an important component of an integrated pest management programme.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] For example: mosquitoes are often controlled by putting *Bt Bacillus thuringiensis* ssp.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] *israelensis*, a bacterium that infects and kills mosquito larvae, in local water sources.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Mechanical pest control is the use of hands-on techniques as well as simple equipment and devices, that provides a protective barrier between plants and insects.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Crop rotation can help to control pests by depriving them of their host plants.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] It is a major tactic in the control of corn rootworm, and has reduced early season incidence of Colorado potato beetle by as much as 95%.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] A trap crop is a crop of a plant that attracts pests, diverting them from nearby crops.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Pests aggregated on the trap crop can be more easily controlled using pesticides or other methods.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] However, trap-cropping, on its own, has often failed to cost effectively reduce pest densities on large commercial scales, without the use of pesticides, possibly due to the pests' ability to disperse back into the main field.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Pesticides are substances applied to crops to control pests, they include herbicides to kill weeds, fungicides to kill fungi and insecticides to kill insects.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Application methods include sprays by hand, tractors, or aircraft or as seed dressings.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] To be effective, the correct substance must be applied at the correct time and the method of application is important to ensure adequate coverage and retention on the crop.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The killing of natural enemies of the target pest should be minimized.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] This is particularly important in countries where there are natural reservoirs of pests and their enemies in the countryside surrounding plantation crops, and these co-exist in a delicate balance.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Often in less-developed countries, the crops are well adapted to the local situation and no pesticides are needed.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Where progressive farmers are using fertilizers to grow improved crop varieties, these are often more susceptible to pest damage, but the indiscriminate application of pesticides may be detrimental in the longer term.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The efficacy of chemical pesticides tends to diminish over time.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] This is because any organism that manages to survive the initial application will pass on its genes to its offspring and a resistant strain will be developed.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] In this way, some of the most serious pests have developed resistance and are no longer killed by pesticides that used to kill their ancestors.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] This necessitates higher concentrations of chemical, more frequent applications and a movement to more expensive formulations.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Pesticides are intended to kill pests, but many have detrimental effects on non-target species; of particular concern is the damage done to honey-bees, solitary bees and other pollinating insects and in this regard, the time of day when the spray is applied can be important.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The widely used neonicotinoids have been banned on flowering crops in some countries because of their effects on bees.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Some pesticides may cause cancer and other health problems in humans, as well as being harmful to wildlife.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] There can be acute effects immediately after exposure or chronic effects after continuous low-level, or occasional exposure.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Maximum residue limits for pesticides in foodstuffs and animal feed are set by many nations.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Using crops with inheritable resistance to pests is referred to as host-plant resistance and reduces the need for pesticide use.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] These crops can harm or even kill pests, repel feeding, prevent colonization, or tolerate the presence of a pest without significantly impacting yield.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Resistance can also occur through genetic engineering to have traits with resistance to insects, such as with Bt corn, or papaya resistance to ringspot virus.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] When farmers are purchasing seed, variety information often includes resistance to selected pests in addition to other traits.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Pest control via hunting, like all forms of harvest, has imposed an artificial selective pressure on the organisms being targeted.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] While varmint hunting is potentially selecting for desired behavioural and demographic changes (e.g. animals avoiding human populated areas, crops and livestock), it can also result in unpredicted outcomes such as the targeted animal adapting for faster reproductive cycles.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Forest pests present a significant problem because it is not easy to access the canopy and monitor pest populations.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] In addition, forestry pests such as bark beetles, kept under control by natural enemies in their native range, may be transported large distances in cut timber to places where they have no natural predators, enabling them to cause extensive economic damage.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Pheromone traps have been used to monitor pest populations in the canopy.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] These release volatile chemicals that attract males.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Pheromone traps can detect the arrival of pests or alert foresters to outbreaks.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] For example, the spruce budworm, a destructive pest of spruce and balsam fir, has been monitored using pheromone traps in Canadian forests for several decades.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] In some regions, such as New Brunswick, areas of forest are sprayed with pesticide to control the budworm population and prevent the damage caused during outbreaks.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Many unwelcome animals visit or make their home in residential buildings, industrial sites and urban areas.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Some contaminate foodstuffs, damage structural timbers, chew through fabrics or infest stored dry goods.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Some inflict great economic loss, others carry diseases or cause fire hazards, and some are just a nuisance.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Control of these pests has been attempted by improving sanitation and garbage control, modifying the habitat, and using repellents, growth regulators, traps, baits and pesticides.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Physical pest control involves trapping or killing pests such as insects and rodents.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Historically, local people or paid rat-catchers caught and killed rodents using dogs and traps.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] On a domestic scale, sticky flypapers are used to trap flies.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] In larger buildings, insects may be trapped using such means as pheromones, synthetic volatile chemicals or ultraviolet light to attract the insects; some have a sticky base or an electrically charged grid to kill them.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Glueboards are sometimes used for monitoring cockroaches and to catch rodents.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Rodents can be killed by suitably baited spring traps and can be caught in cage traps for relocation.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Talcum powder or "tracking powder" can be used to establish routes used by rodents inside buildings and acoustic devices can be used for detecting beetles in structural timbers.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Historically, firearms have been one of the primary methods used for pest control.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] "Garden Guns" are smooth bore shotguns specifically made to fire .22 caliber snake shot or 9mm Flobert, and are commonly used by gardeners and farmers for snakes, rodents, birds, and other pest.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Garden Guns are short-range weapons that can do little harm past 15 to 20 yards, and they're relatively quiet when fired with snake shot, compared to standard ammunition.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] These guns are especially effective inside of barns and sheds, as the snake shot will not shoot holes in the roof or walls, or more importantly, injure livestock with a ricochet.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] They are also used for pest control at airports, warehouses, stockyards, etc.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The most common shot cartridge is .22 Long Rifle loaded with #12 shot.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] At a distance of about 10 ft (3.0 m), which is about the maximum effective range, the pattern is about 8 in (20 cm) in diameter from a standard rifle.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Special smoothbore shotguns, such as the Marlin Model 25MG can produce effective patterns out to 15 or 20 yards using .22 WMR shotshells, which hold 1/8 oz. of #12 shot contained in a plastic capsule.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Poisoned bait is a common method for controlling rats, mice, birds, slugs, snails, ants, cockroaches, and other pests.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The basic granules, or other formulation, contains a food attractant for the target species and a suitable poison.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] For ants, a slow-acting toxin is needed so that the workers have time to carry the substance back to the colony, and for flies, a quick-acting substance to prevent further egg-laying and nuisance.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Baits for slugs and snails often contain the molluscide metaldehyde, dangerous to children and household pets.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] An article in *Scientific American* in 1885 described effective elimination of a cockroach infestation using fresh cucumber peels.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Warfarin has traditionally been used to kill rodents, but many populations have developed resistance to this anticoagulant, and difenacoum may be substituted.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] These are cumulative poisons, requiring bait stations to be topped up regularly.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Poisoned meat has been used for centuries to kill animals such as wolves and birds of prey.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Poisoned carcasses however kill a wide range of carrion feeders, not only the targeted species.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Raptors in Israel were nearly wiped out following a period of intense poisoning of rats and other crop pests.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Fumigation is the treatment of a structure to kill pests such as wood-boring beetles by sealing it or surrounding it with an airtight cover such as a tent, and fogging with liquid insecticide for an extended period, typically of 24–72 hours.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] This is costly and inconvenient as the structure cannot be used during the treatment, but it targets all life stages of pests.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] An alternative, space treatment, is fogging or misting to disperse a liquid insecticide in the atmosphere within a building without evacuation or airtight sealing, allowing most work within the building to continue, at the cost of reduced penetration.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Contact insecticides are generally used to minimize long-lasting residual effects.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Populations of pest insects can sometimes be dramatically reduced by the release of sterile individuals.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] This involves the mass rearing of a pest, sterilising it by means of X-rays or some other means, and releasing it into a wild population.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] It is particularly useful where a female only mates once and where the insect does not disperse widely.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] This technique has been successfully used against the New World screw-worm fly, some species of tsetse fly, tropical fruit flies, the pink bollworm and the codling moth, among others.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] To chemically sterilize pests using chemosterilants, laboratory studies conducted using U-5897 (3-chloro-1,2-propanediol) attempted in the early 1970s for rat control, although these proved unsuccessful.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] In 2013, New York City tested sterilization traps, demonstrating a 43% reduction in rat populations.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The product ContraPest was approved for the sterilization of rodents by the U.S.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Environmental Protection Agency in August 2016 as a chemosterilant.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Boron, a known pesticide can be impregnated into the paper fibers of cellulose insulation at certain levels to achieve a mechanical kill factor for self-grooming insects such as ants, cockroaches, termites, and more.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The addition of insulation into the attic and walls of a structure can provide control of common pests in addition to known insulation benefits such a robust thermal envelope and acoustic noise-canceling properties.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The EPA regulates this type of general-use pesticide within the United States allowing it to only be sold and installed by licensed pest management professionals as part of an integrated pest management program.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Simply adding Boron or an EPA-registered pesticide to an insulation does not qualify it as a pesticide.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] The dosage and method must be carefully controlled and monitored.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Birds are a significant hazard to aircraft, but it is difficult to keep them away from airfields.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Stunning birds by feeding them a bait containing stupefying substances has been tried, and it may be possible to reduce their numbers on airfields by reducing the number of earthworms and other invertebrates by soil treatment.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Leaving the grass long on airfields rather than mowing it is also a deterrent to birds.
[src:eppo-code/crop-protection] Sonic nets are being trialled; these produce sounds that birds find distracting and seem effective at keeping birds away from affected areas.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] A **cultivar** is a kind of cultivated plant that people have selected for desired traits and which retains those traits when propagated.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Methods used to propagate cultivars include division, root and stem cuttings, offsets, grafting, tissue culture, or carefully controlled seed production.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Most cultivars arise from deliberate human manipulation, but some originate from wild plants that have distinctive characteristics.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Cultivar names are chosen according to rules of the International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants (ICNCP), and not all cultivated plants qualify as cultivars.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Horticulturists generally believe the word *cultivar* was coined as a term meaning "**cultivated variety**".
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Popular ornamental plants like roses, camellias, daffodils, rhododendrons, and azaleas are commonly cultivars produced by breeding and selection or as sports, for floral colour or size, plant form, or other desirable characteristics.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Similarly, the world's agricultural food crops are almost exclusively cultivars that have been selected for characters such as improved yield, flavour, and resistance to disease.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Since the advent of genetic engineering in the 1970s and the rise of its application in crop breeding in the 1980s, very few wild plants are used as commercial food sources.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Trees used in forestry are also special selections grown for their enhanced quality and yield of timber, for example American timber company Weyerhaeuser is the leading grower of genetically modified Douglas-fir trees, one of the most commonly harvested trees.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Cultivars form a major part of Liberty Hyde Bailey's broader group, the cultigen, which is defined as a plant whose origin or selection is primarily due to intentional human activity.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] A cultivar is not the same as a botanical variety, which is a taxonomic rank below subspecies, and there are differences in the rules for creating and using the names of botanical varieties and cultivars.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Since the creation of the Plant Patent Act of 1930 the naming of cultivars has been complicated by the use of statutory patents for plants and recognition of plant breeders' rights.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV – French: *Union internationale pour la protection des obtentions végétales*) offers legal protection of plant cultivars to persons or organisations that introduce new cultivars to commerce.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] UPOV requires that a cultivar be "distinct", "uniform", and "stable".
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] To be "distinct", it must have characters that easily distinguish it from any other named cultivar.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] To be "uniform" and "stable", the cultivar must retain these characters in repeated propagation.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The naming of cultivars is an important aspect of cultivated plant taxonomy, and the correct naming of a cultivar is prescribed by the Rules and Recommendations of the *International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants* (ICNCP, often called the *Cultivated Plant Code*).
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] A cultivar is given a cultivar name, which consists of the scientific Latin botanical name followed by a cultivar epithet.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The cultivar epithet is usually in a vernacular language, and must be so for cultivars named after 1 January 1959.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The word *cultivar* originated from the need to distinguish between wild plants and those with characteristics that arose in cultivation, presently denominated *cultigens*.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] This distinction dates to the Greek philosopher Theophrastus (370–285 BC), the "Father of Botany", who was keenly aware of this difference.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants uses as its starting point for modern botanical nomenclature the Latin names in Linnaeus' (1707–1778) *Species Plantarum* (tenth edition) and *Genera Plantarum* (fifth edition).
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] In *Species Plantarum*, Linnaeus enumerated all plants known to him, either directly or from his extensive reading.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] He recognised the rank of varietas (botanical "variety", a rank below that of species and subspecies) and he indicated these varieties with letters of the Greek alphabet, such as α, β, and δ, before the varietal name, rather than using the abbreviation "var." as is the present convention.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Most of the varieties that Linnaeus enumerated were of "garden" origin rather than being wild plants.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] In time the need to distinguish between wild plants and those with variations that had been cultivated increased.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] In the nineteenth century many "garden-derived" plants were given horticultural names, sometimes in Latin and sometimes in a vernacular language.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] From *circa* the 1900s, cultivated plants in Europe were recognised in the Scandinavian, Germanic, and Slavic literature as *stamm* or *sorte*, but these words could not be used internationally because, by international agreement, any new denominations had to be in Latin.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] In the twentieth century an improved international nomenclature was proposed for cultivated plants.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] In that essay, Bailey used only the rank of species for the cultigen, but it was obvious to him that many domesticated plants were more like botanical varieties than species, and that realisation appears to have motivated the suggestion of the new category of *cultivar*.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] It is generally assumed to be a blend of ***culti**vated* and ***var**iety* but Bailey never explicitly stated his choice of etymology, and it has been suggested that the word is actually a blend of ***culti**gen* and ***var**iety*.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The neologism *cultivar* was promoted as "euphonious" and "free from ambiguity".
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The first *Cultivated Plant Code* of 1953 subsequently commended its use, and by 1960 it had achieved common international acceptance.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The words *cultigen* and *cultivar* may be confused with each other.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] A *cultigen* is any plant that is deliberately selected for or altered in cultivation, as opposed to an *indigen*; the *Cultivated Plant Code* states that cultigens are "maintained as recognisable entities solely by continued propagation".
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Cultigens can have names at any of many taxonomic ranks, including those of grex, species, cultivar group, variety, form, and cultivar; and they may be plants that have been altered in cultivation, including by genetic modification, but have not been formally denominated.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] A cultigen or a component of a cultigen can be accepted as a cultivar if it is recognisable and has stable characters.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Therefore, all cultivars are cultigens, because they are cultivated, but not all cultigens are cultivars, because some cultigens have not been formally distinguished and named as cultivars.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The *Code* then defines a *cultivar* as a "taxonomic unit within the classification category of cultivar".
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] This is the sense of *cultivar* that is most generally understood and which is used as a general definition.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] A cultivar may be given a vernacular name or a number.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Which plants are chosen to be named as cultivars is simply a matter of convenience as the category was created to serve the practical needs of horticulture, agriculture, and forestry.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Members of a particular cultivar are not necessarily genetically identical.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The *Cultivated Plant Code* emphasizes that different cultivated plants may be accepted as different cultivars, even if they have the same genome, while cultivated plants with different genomes may be regarded as the same cultivar.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The production of cultivars generally entails considerable human involvement although in a few cases it may be as little as simply selecting variation from plants growing in the wild (whether by collecting growing tissue to propagate from or by gathering seed).
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Cultivars generally occur as ornamentals and food crops: *Malus* 'Granny Smith' and *Malus* 'Red Delicious' are cultivars of apples propagated by cuttings or grafting, *Lactuca* 'Red Sails' and *Lactuca* 'Great Lakes' are lettuce cultivars propagated by seeds.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Named cultivars of *Hosta* and *Hemerocallis* plants are cultivars produced by micropropagation or division.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Cultivars that are produced asexually are genetically identical and known as clones; this includes plants propagated by division, layering, cuttings, grafts, and budding.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The propagating material may be taken from a particular part of the plant, such as a lateral branch, or from a particular phase of the life cycle, such as a juvenile leaf, or from aberrant growth as occurs with witch's broom.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Plants whose distinctive characters are derived from the presence of an intracellular organism may also form a cultivar provided the characters are reproduced reliably from generation to generation.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Plants of the same chimera (which have mutant tissues close to normal tissue) or graft-chimeras (which have vegetative tissue from different kinds of plants and which originate by grafting) may also constitute a cultivar.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Some cultivars "come true from seed", retaining their distinguishing characteristics when grown from seed.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Such plants are termed a "variety", "selection", or "strain" but these are ambiguous and confusing words that are best avoided.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] In general, asexually propagated cultivars grown from seeds produce highly variable seedling plants, and should not be labelled with, or sold under, the parent cultivar's name.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Seed-raised cultivars may be produced by uncontrolled pollination when characteristics that are distinct, uniform and stable are passed from parents to progeny.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Some are produced as "lines" that are produced by repeated self-fertilisation or inbreeding or "multilines" that are made up of several closely related lines.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Sometimes they are F1 hybrids which are the result of a deliberate repeatable single cross between two pure lines.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] A few F2 hybrid seed cultivars also exist, such as *Achillea* 'Summer Berries'.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Some cultivars are agamospermous plants, which retain their genetic composition and characteristics under reproduction.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Occasionally cultivars are raised from seed of a specially selected provenance – for example the seed may be taken from plants that are resistant to a particular disease.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Genetically modified plants with characteristics resulting from the deliberate implantation of genetic material from a different germplasm may form a cultivar.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] However, the International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants notes, "In practice such an assemblage is often marketed from one or more lines or multilines that have been genetically modified.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Cultivars may be selected because of a change in the ploidy level of a plant which may produce more desirable characteristics.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Every cultivar has a unique name within its denomination class (which is almost always the genus).
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Names of cultivars are regulated by the *International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants*, and may be registered with an International Cultivar Registration Authority (ICRA).
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] There are sometimes separate registration authorities for different plant types such as roses and camellias.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] In addition, cultivars may be associated with commercial marketing names referred to in the *Cultivated Plant Code* as "trade designations" (see below).
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] A *cultivar name* consists of a botanical name (of a genus, species, infraspecific taxon, interspecific hybrid or intergeneric hybrid) followed by a cultivar epithet.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The cultivar epithet is enclosed by single quotes; it should not be italicised if the botanical name is italicised; and each of the words within the epithet is capitalised (with some permitted exceptions such as conjunctions).
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] It is permissible to place a cultivar epithet after a common name provided the common name is botanically unambiguous.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Cultivar epithets published before 1 January 1959 were often given a Latin form and can be readily confused with the specific epithets in botanical names; after that date, newly coined cultivar epithets must be in a modern vernacular language to distinguish them from botanical epithets.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] For example, the full cultivar name of the King Edward potato is *Solanum tuberosum* 'King Edward'.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] 'King Edward' is the cultivar epithet, which, according to the Rules of the *Cultivated Plant Code*, is bounded by single quotation marks.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Although "cv." has not been permitted by the International Code of Nomenclature for Cultivated Plants since the 1995 edition, it is still widely used and recommended by other authorities.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Where several very similar cultivars exist they can be associated into a *Group* (formerly *Cultivar-group*).
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] As Group names are used with cultivar names it is necessary to understand their way of presentation.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Group names are presented in normal type and the first letter of each word capitalised as for cultivars, but they are not placed in single quotes.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] When used in a name, the first letter of the word "Group" is itself capitalised.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Since the 1990s there has been an increasing use of legal protection for newly produced cultivars.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Plant breeders expect legal protection for the cultivars they produce.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] According to proponents of such protections, if other growers can immediately propagate and sell these cultivars as soon as they come on the market, the breeder's benefit is largely lost.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Legal protection for cultivars is obtained through the use of Plant breeders' rights and plant Patents but the specific legislation and procedures needed to take advantage of this protection vary from country to country.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The use of legal protection for cultivars can be controversial, particularly for food crops that are staples in developing countries, or for plants selected from the wild and propagated for sale without any additional breeding work; some people consider this practice unethical.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The formal scientific name of a cultivar, like *Solanum tuberosum* 'King Edward', is a way of uniquely designating a particular kind of plant.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] This scientific name is in the public domain and cannot be legally protected.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Plant retailers may wish to increase their share of the market, and one way of doing this is to replace the Latin scientific names on plant labels in retail outlets with appealing marketing names that are easy to use, pronounce, and remember.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Marketing names lie outside the scope of the *Cultivated Plant Code* which refers to them as "trade designations".
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] If a retailer or wholesaler has the sole legal rights to a marketing name then that may offer a sales advantage.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Plants protected by plant breeders' rights (PBR) may have a "true" cultivar name – the accepted scientific name in the public domain – and a "commercial synonym" – an additional marketing name that is legally protected.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] An example would be *Rosa* Fascination='Poulmax', in which *Rosa* is the genus, Fascination is the trade designation, and 'Poulmax' is scientific cultivar name.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Because a name that is attractive in one language may have less appeal in another country, a plant may be given different selling names from country to country.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Quoting the original cultivar name allows the correct identification of cultivars around the world.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The main body coordinating plant breeders' rights is the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (*Union internationale pour la protection des obtentions végétales*, UPOV) and this organisation maintains a database of new cultivars protected by PBR in all countries.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] An *International Cultivar Registration Authority* (ICRA) is a voluntary, non-statutory organisation appointed by the *Commission for Nomenclature and Cultivar Registration* of the International Society of Horticultural Science.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] ICRAs are generally formed by societies and institutions specializing in particular plant genera such as *Dahlia* or *Rhododendron* and are currently located in Europe, North America, China, India, Singapore, Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and Puerto Rico.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Each ICRA produces an annual report and its reappointment is considered every four years.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The main task is to maintain a register of the names within the group of interest and where possible this is published and placed in the public domain.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] One major aim is to prevent the duplication of cultivar and Group epithets within a genus, as well as ensuring that names are in accord with the latest edition of the *Cultivated Plant Code*.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] In this way, over the last 50 years or so, ICRAs have contributed to the stability of cultivated plant nomenclature.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] In recent times many ICRAs have also recorded trade designations and trademarks used in labelling plant material, to avoid confusion with established names.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] New names and other relevant data are collected by and submitted to the ICRA and in most cases there is no cost.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] The ICRA then checks each new epithet to ensure that it has not been used before and that it conforms with the *Cultivated Plant Code*.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Each ICRA also ensures that new names are formally established (i.e. published in hard copy, with a description in a dated publication).
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] They record details about the plant, such as parentage, the names of those concerned with its development and introduction, and a basic description highlighting its distinctive characters.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] ICRAs are not responsible for assessing the distinctiveness of the plant in question.
[src:eppo-code/cultivar] Most ICRAs can be contacted electronically and many maintain web sites for an up-to-date listing.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In computing, a **database** is an organized collection of data or a type of data store based on the use of a **database management system** (**DBMS**), the software that interacts with end users, applications, and the database itself to capture and analyze the data.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The DBMS additionally encompasses the core facilities provided to administer the database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The sum total of the database, the DBMS and the associated applications can be referred to as a **database system**.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Often the term "database" is also used loosely to refer to any of the DBMS, the database system or an application associated with the database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Professional book indexers used index cards in the creation of book indexes until they were replaced by indexing software in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Small databases can be stored on a file system, while large databases are hosted on computer clusters or cloud storage.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The design of databases spans formal techniques and practical considerations, including data modeling, efficient data representation and storage, query languages, security and privacy of sensitive data, and distributed computing issues, including supporting concurrent access and fault tolerance.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Computer scientists may classify database management systems according to the database models that they support.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Relational databases became dominant in the 1980s.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] These model data as rows and columns in a series of tables, and the vast majority use SQL for writing and querying data.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In the 2000s, non-relational databases became popular, collectively referred to as NoSQL, because they use different query languages.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The DBMS provides various functions that allow entry, storage and retrieval of large quantities of information and provides ways to manage how that information is organized.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Because of the close relationship between them, the term "database" is often used casually to refer to both a database and the DBMS used to manipulate it.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Outside the world of professional information technology, the term *database* is often used to refer to any collection of related data (such as a spreadsheet or a card index) as size and usage requirements typically necessitate use of a database management system.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Both a database and its DBMS conform to the principles of a particular database model.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] "Database system" refers collectively to the database model, database management system, and database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Physically, database servers are dedicated computers that hold the actual databases and run only the DBMS and related software.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Database servers are usually multiprocessor computers, with generous memory and RAID disk arrays used for stable storage.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Hardware database accelerators, connected to one or more servers via a high-speed channel, are also used in large-volume transaction processing environments.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] DBMSs are found at the heart of most database applications.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] DBMSs may be built around a custom multitasking kernel with built-in networking support, but modern DBMSs typically rely on a standard operating system to provide these functions.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Since DBMSs comprise a significant market, computer and storage vendors often take into account DBMS requirements in their own development plans.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The sizes, capabilities, and performance of databases and their respective DBMSs have grown in orders of magnitude.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] These performance increases were enabled by the technology progress in the areas of processors, computer memory, computer storage, and computer networks.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The concept of a database was made possible by the emergence of direct access storage media such as magnetic disks, which became widely available in the mid-1960s; earlier systems relied on sequential storage of data on magnetic tape.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The subsequent development of database technology can be divided into three eras based on data model or structure: navigational, SQL/relational, and post-relational.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The two main early navigational data models were the hierarchical model and the CODASYL model (network model).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] These were characterized by the use of pointers (often physical disk addresses) to follow relationships from one record to another.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The relational model, first proposed in 1970 by Edgar F.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Codd, departed from this tradition by insisting that applications should search for data by content, rather than by following links.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The relational model employs sets of ledger-style tables, each used for a different type of entity.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Only in the mid-1980s did computing hardware become powerful enough to allow the wide deployment of relational systems (DBMSs plus applications).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] By the early 1990s, however, relational systems dominated in all large-scale data processing applications, and as of 2018 they remain dominant: IBM Db2, Oracle, MySQL, and Microsoft SQL Server are the most searched DBMS.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The dominant database language, standardized SQL for the relational model, has influenced database languages for other data models.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Object databases were developed in the 1980s to overcome the inconvenience of object–relational impedance mismatch, which led to the coining of the term "post-relational" and also the development of hybrid object–relational databases.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The next generation of post-relational databases in the late 2000s became known as NoSQL databases, introducing fast key–value stores and document-oriented databases.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] A competing "next generation" known as NewSQL databases attempted new implementations that retained the relational/SQL model while aiming to match the high performance of NoSQL compared to commercially available relational DBMSs.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The introduction of the term *database* coincided with the availability of direct-access storage (disks and drums) from the mid-1960s onwards.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The term represented a contrast with the tape-based systems of the past, allowing shared interactive use rather than daily batch processing.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The Oxford English Dictionary cites a 1962 report by the System Development Corporation of California as the first to use the term "data-base" in a specific technical sense.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] As computers grew in speed and capability, a number of general-purpose database systems emerged; by the mid-1960s a number of such systems had come into commercial use.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Interest in a standard began to grow, and Charles Bachman, author of one such product, the Integrated Data Store (IDS), founded the Database Task Group within CODASYL, the group responsible for the creation and standardization of COBOL.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In 1971, the Database Task Group delivered their standard, which generally became known as the *CODASYL approach*, and soon a number of commercial products based on this approach entered the market.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The CODASYL approach offered applications the ability to navigate around a linked data set which was formed into a large network.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Later systems added B-trees to provide alternate access paths.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Many CODASYL databases also added a declarative query language for end users (as distinct from the navigational API).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] However, CODASYL databases were complex and required significant training and effort to produce useful applications.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] IBM also had its own DBMS in 1966, known as Information Management System (IMS).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] IMS was a development of software written for the Apollo program on the System/360.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] IMS was generally similar in concept to CODASYL, but used a strict hierarchy for its model of data navigation instead of CODASYL's network model.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Both concepts later became known as navigational databases due to the way data was accessed: the term was popularized by Bachman's 1973 Turing Award presentation *The Programmer as Navigator*.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] IMS is classified by IBM as a hierarchical database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] IDMS and Cincom Systems' TOTAL databases are classified as network databases.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Codd worked at IBM in San Jose, California, in an office primarily involved in the development of hard disk systems.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] He was unhappy with the navigational model of the CODASYL approach, notably the lack of a "search" facility.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In 1970, he wrote a number of papers that outlined a new approach to database construction that eventually culminated in the groundbreaking *A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks*.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The paper described a new system for storing and working with large databases.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Instead of records being stored in some sort of linked list of free-form records as in CODASYL, Codd's idea was to organize the data as a number of "tables", each table being used for a different type of entity.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Each table would contain a fixed number of columns containing the attributes of the entity.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Splitting the data into a set of normalized tables (or *relations*) aimed to ensure that each "fact" was only stored once, thus simplifying update operations.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Virtual tables called *views* could present the data in different ways for different users, but views could not be directly updated.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Codd used mathematical terms to define the model: relations, tuples, and domains rather than tables, rows, and columns.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The terminology that is now familiar came from early implementations.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Codd would later criticize the tendency for practical implementations to depart from the mathematical foundations on which the model was based.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The use of primary keys (user-oriented identifiers) to represent cross-table relationships, rather than disk addresses, had two primary motivations.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] From an engineering perspective, it enabled tables to be relocated and resized without expensive database reorganization.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] There is no loss of expressiveness compared with the hierarchic or network models, though the connections between tables are no longer so explicit.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In the hierarchic and network models, records were allowed to have a complex internal structure.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] For example, the salary history of an employee might be represented as a "repeating group" within the employee record.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In the relational model, the process of normalization led to such internal structures being replaced by data held in multiple tables, connected only by logical keys.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] For instance, a common use of a database system is to track information about users, their name, login information, various addresses and phone numbers.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In the navigational approach, all of this data would be placed in a single variable-length record.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In the relational approach, the data would be *normalized* into a user table, an address table and a phone number table (for instance).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Records would be created in these optional tables only if the address or phone numbers were actually provided.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] As well as identifying rows/records using logical identifiers rather than disk addresses, Codd changed the way in which applications assembled data from multiple records.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Rather than requiring applications to gather data one record at a time by navigating the links, they would use a declarative query language that expressed what data was required, rather than the access path by which it should be found.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Finding an efficient access path to the data became the responsibility of the database management system, rather than the application programmer.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] This process, called query optimization, depended on the fact that queries were expressed in terms of mathematical logic.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Beginning in 1973, INGRES delivered its first test products which were generally ready for widespread use in 1979.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] INGRES was similar to System R in a number of ways, including the use of a "language" for data access, known as QUEL.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Over time, INGRES moved to the emerging SQL standard.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] IBM itself did one test implementation of the relational model, PRTV, and a production one, Business System 12, both now discontinued.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Honeywell wrote MRDS for Multics, and now there are two new implementations: Alphora Dataphor and Rel.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Most other DBMS implementations usually called *relational* are actually SQL DBMSs.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In 1970, the University of Michigan began development of the MICRO Information Management System based on D.L.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The university in 1974 hosted a debate between Codd and Bachman which Bruce Lindsay of IBM later described as "throwing lightning bolts at each other!".
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] MICRO was used to manage very large data sets by the US Department of Labor, the U.S.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Environmental Protection Agency, and researchers from the University of Alberta, the University of Michigan, and Wayne State University.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] It ran on IBM mainframe computers using the Michigan Terminal System.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The system remained in production until 1998.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, attempts were made to build database systems with integrated hardware and software.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The underlying philosophy was that such integration would provide higher performance at a lower cost.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Examples were IBM System/38, the early offering of Teradata, and the Britton Lee, Inc. database machine.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Another approach to hardware support for database management was ICL's CAFS accelerator, a hardware disk controller with programmable search capabilities.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In the long term, these efforts were generally unsuccessful because specialized database machines could not keep pace with the rapid development and progress of general-purpose computers.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Thus most database systems nowadays are software systems running on general-purpose hardware, using general-purpose computer data storage.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] However, this idea is still pursued in certain applications by some companies like Netezza and Oracle (Exadata).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] IBM formed a team led by Codd that started working on a prototype system, *System R* despite opposition from others at the company.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The first version was ready in 1974/5, and work then started on multi-table systems in which the data could be split so that all of the data for a record (some of which is optional) did not have to be stored in a single large "chunk".
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Subsequent multi-user versions were tested by customers in 1978 and 1979, by which time a standardized query language – SQL – had been added.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Codd's ideas were establishing themselves as both workable and superior to CODASYL, pushing IBM to develop a true production version of System R, known as *SQL/DS*, and, later, *Database 2* (IBM Db2).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Larry Ellison's Oracle Database (or more simply, Oracle) started from a different chain, based on IBM's papers on System R.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Though Oracle V1 implementations were completed in 1978, it was not until Oracle Version 2 when Ellison beat IBM to market in 1979.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Stonebraker went on to apply the lessons from INGRES to develop a new database, Postgres, which is now known as PostgreSQL.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] PostgreSQL is often used for global mission-critical applications (the .org and .info domain name registries use it as their primary data store, as do many large companies and financial institutions).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In Sweden, Codd's paper was also read and Mimer SQL was developed in the mid-1970s at Uppsala University.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In 1984, this project was consolidated into an independent enterprise.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Another data model, the entity–relationship model, emerged in 1976 and gained popularity for database design as it emphasized a more familiar description than the earlier relational model.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Later on, entity–relationship constructs were retrofitted as a data modeling construct for the relational model, and the difference between the two has become irrelevant.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Besides IBM and various software companies such as Sybase and Informix Corporation, most large computer hardware vendors by the 1980s had their own database systems such as DEC's VAX Rdb/VMS.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The decade ushered in the age of desktop computing.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The new computers empowered their users with spreadsheets like Lotus 1-2-3 and database software like dBASE.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The dBASE product was lightweight and easy for any computer user to understand out of the box.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Wayne Ratliff, the creator of dBASE, stated: "dBASE was different from programs like BASIC, C, FORTRAN, and COBOL in that a lot of the dirty work had already been done.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] By the start of the decade databases had become a billion-dollar industry in about ten years.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The 1990s, along with a rise in object-oriented programming, saw a growth in how data in various databases were handled.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Programmers and designers began to treat the data in their databases as objects.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] That is to say that if a person's data were in a database, that person's attributes, such as their address, phone number, and age, were now considered to belong to that person instead of being extraneous data.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] This allows for relations between data to be related to objects and their attributes and not to individual fields.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The term "object–relational impedance mismatch" described the inconvenience of translating between programmed objects and database tables.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Object databases and object–relational databases attempt to solve this problem by providing an object-oriented language (sometimes as extensions to SQL) that programmers can use as alternative to purely relational SQL.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] On the programming side, libraries known as object–relational mappings (ORMs) attempt to solve the same problem.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Database sales grew rapidly during the dotcom bubble and, after its end, the rise of ecommerce.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The popularity of open source databases such as MySQL has grown since 2000, to the extent that Ken Jacobs of Oracle said in 2005 that perhaps "these guys are doing to us what we did to IBM".
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] XML databases are a type of structured document-oriented database that allows querying based on XML document attributes.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] XML databases are mostly used in applications where the data is conveniently viewed as a collection of documents, with a structure that can vary from the very flexible to the highly rigid: examples include scientific articles, patents, tax filings, and personnel records.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] NoSQL databases are often very fast, do not require fixed table schemas, avoid join operations by storing denormalized data, and are designed to scale horizontally.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Some NoSQL databases, including graph databases such as Neo4j, represent data as nodes and edges to model relationships between entities.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In recent years, there has been a strong demand for massively distributed databases with high partition tolerance, but according to the CAP theorem, it is impossible for a distributed system to simultaneously provide consistency, availability, and partition tolerance guarantees.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] A distributed system can satisfy any two of these guarantees at the same time, but not all three.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] For that reason, many NoSQL databases are using what is called eventual consistency to provide both availability and partition tolerance guarantees with a reduced level of data consistency.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] NewSQL is a class of modern relational databases that aims to provide the same scalable performance of NoSQL systems for online transaction processing (read-write) workloads while still using SQL and maintaining the ACID guarantees of a traditional database system.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Databases are used to support internal operations of organizations and to underpin online interactions with customers and suppliers (see Enterprise software).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Databases are used to hold administrative information and more specialized data, such as engineering data or economic models.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Examples include computerized library systems, flight reservation systems, computerized parts inventory systems, and many content management systems that store websites as collections of webpages in a database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] One way to classify databases involves the type of their contents, for example: bibliographic, document-text, statistical, or multimedia objects.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Another way is by their application area, for example: accounting, music compositions, movies, banking, manufacturing, or insurance.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] A third way is by some technical aspect, such as the database structure or interface type.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] This section lists a few of the adjectives used to characterize different kinds of databases.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database." Examples of DBMS's include MySQL, MariaDB, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, Oracle Database, and Microsoft Access.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The DBMS acronym is sometimes extended to indicate the underlying database model, with RDBMS for the relational, OODBMS for the object (oriented) and ORDBMS for the object–relational model.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Other extensions can indicate some other characteristics, such as DDBMS for a distributed database management systems.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The functionality provided by a DBMS can vary enormously.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The core functionality is the storage, retrieval and update of data.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] It is also generally to be expected the DBMS will provide a set of utilities for such purposes as may be necessary to administer the database effectively, including import, export, monitoring, defragmentation and analysis utilities.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The core part of the DBMS interacting between the database and the application interface sometimes referred to as the database engine.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Often DBMSs will have configuration parameters that can be statically and dynamically tuned, for example the maximum amount of main memory on a server the database can use.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The trend is to minimize the amount of manual configuration, and for cases such as embedded databases the need to target zero-administration is paramount.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The large major enterprise DBMSs have tended to increase in size and functionality and have involved up to thousands of human years of development effort throughout their lifetime.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Early multi-user DBMS typically only allowed for the application to reside on the same computer with access via terminals or terminal emulation software.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The client–server architecture was a development where the application resided on a client desktop and the database on a server allowing the processing to be distributed.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] This evolved into a multitier architecture incorporating application servers and web servers with the end user interface via a web browser with the database only directly connected to the adjacent tier.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] A general-purpose DBMS will provide public application programming interfaces (API) and optionally a processor for database languages such as SQL to allow applications to be written to interact with and manipulate the database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] A special purpose DBMS may use a private API and be specifically customized and linked to a single application.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] For example, an email system performs many of the functions of a general-purpose DBMS such as message insertion, message deletion, attachment handling, blocklist lookup, associating messages an email address and so forth however these functions are limited to what is required to handle email.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] External interaction with the database will be via an application program that interfaces with the DBMS.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] This can range from a database tool that allows users to execute SQL queries textually or graphically, to a website that happens to use a database to store and search information.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] A programmer will code interactions to the database (sometimes referred to as a datasource) via an application program interface (API) or via a database language.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The particular API or language chosen will need to be supported by DBMS, possibly indirectly via a preprocessor or a bridging API.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Some API's aim to be database independent, ODBC being a commonly known example.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Other common API's include JDBC and ADO.NET.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Database languages are specific to a particular data model.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Database storage is the container of the physical materialization of a database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] It comprises the *internal* (physical) *level* in the database architecture.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] It also contains all the information needed (e.g., metadata, "data about the data", and internal data structures) to reconstruct the *conceptual level* and *external level* from the internal level when needed.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Databases as digital objects contain three layers of information which must be stored: the data, the structure, and the semantics.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Proper storage of all three layers is needed for future preservation and longevity of the database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Putting data into permanent storage is generally the responsibility of the database engine a.k.a.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] A DBMS, while in operation, always has its database residing in several types of storage (e.g., memory and external storage).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The database data and the additional needed information, possibly in very large amounts, are coded into bits.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Some DBMSs support specifying which character encoding was used to store data, so multiple encodings can be used in the same database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Various low-level database storage structures are used by the storage engine to serialize the data model so it can be written to the medium of choice.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Techniques such as indexing may be used to improve performance.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Conventional storage is row-oriented, but there are also column-oriented and correlation databases.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Often storage redundancy is employed to increase performance.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] A common example is storing *materialized views*, which consist of frequently needed *external views* or query results.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Storing such views saves the expensive computing them each time they are needed.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] The downsides of materialized views are the overhead incurred when updating them to keep them synchronized with their original updated database data, and the cost of storage redundancy.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Updates of a replicated object need to be synchronized across the object copies.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] In many cases, the entire database is replicated.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Database security deals with all various aspects of protecting the database content, its owners, and its users.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] It ranges from protection from intentional unauthorized database uses to unintentional database accesses by unauthorized entities (e.g., a person or a computer program).
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Database access control deals with controlling who (a person or a certain computer program) are allowed to access what information in the database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Database access controls are set by special authorized (by the database owner) personnel that uses dedicated protected security DBMS interfaces.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] This may be managed directly on an individual basis, or by the assignment of individuals and privileges to groups, or (in the most elaborate models) through the assignment of individuals and groups to roles which are then granted entitlements.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Data security prevents unauthorized users from viewing or updating the database.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] Using passwords, users are allowed access to the entire database or subsets of it called "subschemas".
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] For example, an employee database can contain all the data about an individual employee, but one group of users may be authorized to view only payroll data, while others are allowed access to only work history and medical data.
[src:eppo-code/database-p01] If the DBMS provides a way to interactively enter and update the database, as well as interrogate it, this capability allows for managing personal databases.
